# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: plc-scada
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Automation includes the use of various equipment and control systems such as machinery, processes in factories, boilers, and heat-treating ovens, switching on telephone networks, steering, stabilization of ships, aircraft and other applications and vehicles with reduced human intervention.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Examples range from a household thermostat controlling a boiler to a large industrial control system with tens of thousands of input measurements and output control signals.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In the simplest type of an automatic control loop, a controller compares a measured value of a process with a desired set value and processes the resulting error signal to change some input to the process, in such a way that the process stays at its set point despite disturbances.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] This closed-loop control is an application of negative feedback to a system.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The mathematical basis of control theory began in the 18th century and advanced rapidly in the 20th.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The term *automation*, inspired by the earlier word *automatic* (coming from *automaton*), was not widely used before 1947, when Ford established an automation department.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] It was during this time that the industry was rapidly adopting feedback controllers, Technological advancements introduced in the 1930s revolutionized various industries significantly.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The World Bank's World Development Report of 2019 shows evidence that the new industries and jobs in the technology sector outweigh the economic effects of workers being displaced by automation.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Job losses and downward mobility blamed on automation have been cited as one of many factors in the resurgence of nationalist, protectionist and populist politics in the US, UK and France, among other countries since the 2010s.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] It was a preoccupation of the Greeks and Arabs (in the period between about 300 BC and about 1200 AD) to keep an accurate track of time.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In Ptolemaic Egypt, about 270 BC, Ctesibius described a float regulator for a water clock, a device not unlike the ball and cock in a modern flush toilet.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] This was the earliest feedback-controlled mechanism.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The appearance of the mechanical clock in the 14th century made the water clock and its feedback control system obsolete.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The Persian Banū Mūsā brothers, in their *Book of Ingenious Devices* (850 AD), described a number of automatic controls.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Two-step level controls for fluids, a form of discontinuous variable structure controls, were developed by the Banu Musa brothers.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] They also described a feedback controller.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The design of feedback control systems up through the Industrial Revolution was by trial-and-error, together with a great deal of engineering intuition.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] It was not until the mid-19th century that the stability of feedback control systems was analyzed using mathematics, the formal language of automatic control theory.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the seventeenth century, and used to adjust the gap between millstones.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Another control mechanism was used to tent the sails of windmills.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Also in 1745, Jacques de Vaucanson invented the first automated loom.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Around 1800, Joseph Marie Jacquard created a punch-card system to program looms.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In 1771 Richard Arkwright invented the first fully automated spinning mill driven by water power, known at the time as the water frame.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] An automatic flour mill was developed by Oliver Evans in 1785, making it the first completely automated industrial process.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Bunce of England in 1784 as part of a model steam crane.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was adopted by James Watt for use on a steam engine in 1788 after Watt's partner Boulton saw one at a flour mill Boulton & Watt were building.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The governor could not actually hold a set speed; the engine would assume a new constant speed in response to load changes.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The governor was able to handle smaller variations such as those caused by fluctuating heat load to the boiler.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Also, there was a tendency for oscillation whenever there was a speed change.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] As a consequence, engines equipped with this governor were not suitable for operations requiring constant speed, such as cotton spinning.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Several improvements to the governor, plus improvements to valve cut-off timing on the steam engine, made the engine suitable for most industrial uses before the end of the 19th century.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Advances in the steam engine stayed well ahead of science, both thermodynamics and control theory.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The governor received relatively little scientific attention until James Clerk Maxwell published a paper that established the beginning of a theoretical basis for understanding control theory.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Relay logic was introduced with factory electrification, which underwent rapid adaptation from 1900 through the 1920s.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Central electric power stations were also undergoing rapid growth and the operation of new high-pressure boilers, steam turbines and electrical substations created a great demand for instruments and controls.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Central control rooms became common in the 1920s, but as late as the early 1930s, most process controls were on-off.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Operators typically monitored charts drawn by recorders that plotted data from instruments.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] To make corrections, operators manually opened or closed valves or turned switches on or off.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Control rooms also used color-coded lights to send signals to workers in the plant to manually make certain changes.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The development of the electronic amplifier during the 1920s, which was important for long-distance telephony, required a higher signal-to-noise ratio, which was solved by negative feedback noise cancellation.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] This and other telephony applications contributed to the control theory.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic controls, which found military applications during the Second World War to fire control systems and aircraft navigation systems.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Controllers, which were able to make calculated changes in response to deviations from a set point rather than on-off control, began being introduced in the 1930s.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Controllers allowed manufacturing to continue showing productivity gains to offset the declining influence of factory electrification.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Factory productivity was greatly increased by electrification in the 1920s.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Alexander Field notes that spending on non-medical instruments increased significantly from 1929 to 1933 and remained strong thereafter.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The First and Second World Wars saw major advancements in the field of mass communication and signal processing.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Other key advances in automatic controls include differential equations, stability theory and system theory (1938), frequency domain analysis (1940), ship control (1950), and stochastic analysis (1941).
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In 1959 Texaco's Port Arthur Refinery became the first chemical plant to use digital control.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Conversion of factories to digital control began to spread rapidly in the 1970s as the price of computer hardware fell.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The automatic telephone switchboard was introduced in 1892 along with dial telephones.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] By 1929, 31.9% of the Bell system was automatic.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Automatic telephone switching originally used vacuum tube amplifiers and electro-mechanical switches, which consumed a large amount of electricity.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Call volume eventually grew so fast that it was feared the telephone system would consume all electricity production, prompting Bell Labs to begin research on the transistor.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The logic performed by telephone switching relays was the inspiration for the digital computer.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The first commercially successful glass bottle-blowing machine was an automatic model introduced in 1905.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The machine, operated by a two-man crew working 12-hour shifts, could produce 17,280 bottles in 24 hours, compared to 2,880 bottles made by a crew of six men and boys working in a shop for a day.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The cost of making bottles by machine was 10 to 12 cents per gross compared to $1.80 per gross by the manual glassblowers and helpers.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives were developed using control theory.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives are used on different sections of a machine where a precise differential must be maintained between the sections.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In steel rolling, the metal elongates as it passes through pairs of rollers, which must run at successively faster speeds.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In paper making paper, the sheet shrinks as it passes around steam-heated drying arranged in groups, which must run at successively slower speeds.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The first application of a sectional electric drive was on a paper machine in 1919.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] One of the most important developments in the steel industry during the 20th century was continuous wide strip rolling, developed by Armco in 1928.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Before automation, many chemicals were made in batches.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In 1930, with the widespread use of instruments and the emerging use of controllers, the founder of Dow Chemical Co. was advocating continuous production.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Self-acting machine tools that displaced hand dexterity so they could be operated by boys and unskilled laborers were developed by James Nasmyth in the 1840s.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Machine tools were automated with Numerical control (NC) using punched paper tape in the 1950s.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] This soon evolved into computerized numerical control (CNC).
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Today extensive automation is practiced in practically every type of manufacturing and assembly process.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Robots are especially useful in hazardous applications like automobile spray painting.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Robots are also used to assemble electronic circuit boards.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Automotive welding is done with robots and automatic welders are used in applications like pipelines.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] With the advent of the space age in 1957, controls design, particularly in the United States, turned away from the frequency-domain techniques of classical control theory and backed into the differential equation techniques of the late 19th century, which were couched in the time domain.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] During the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flugge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control, which became widely used in hysteresis control systems such as navigation systems, fire-control systems, and electronics.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Through Flugge-Lotz and others, the modern era saw time-domain design for nonlinear systems (1961), navigation (1960), optimal control and estimation theory (1962), nonlinear control theory (1969), digital control and filtering theory (1974), and the personal computer (1983).
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Perhaps the most cited advantage of automation in industry is that it is associated with faster production and cheaper labor costs.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Another benefit could be that it replaces hard, physical, or monotonous work.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Additionally, tasks that take place in hazardous environments or that are otherwise beyond human capabilities can be done by machines, as machines can operate even under extreme temperatures or in atmospheres that are radioactive or toxic.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] They can also be maintained with simple quality checks.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] However, at the time being, not all tasks can be automated, and some tasks are more expensive to automate than others.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Initial costs of installing the machinery in factory settings are high, and failure to maintain a system could result in the loss of the product itself.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Automation primarily describes machines replacing human action, but it is also loosely associated with mechanization, machines replacing human labor.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The paradox of automation says that the more efficient the automated system, the more crucial the human contribution of the operators.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Humans are less involved, but their involvement becomes more critical.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Lisanne Bainbridge, a cognitive psychologist, identified these issues notably in her widely cited paper "Ironies of Automation." If an automated system has an error, it will multiply that error until it is fixed or shut down.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] A fatal example of this was Air France Flight 447, where a failure of automation put the pilots into a manual situation they were not prepared for.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Many roles for humans in industrial processes presently lie beyond the scope of automation.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Human-level pattern recognition, language comprehension, and language production ability are well beyond the capabilities of modern mechanical and computer systems (but see *Watson computer*).
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Tasks requiring subjective assessment or synthesis of complex sensory data, such as scents and sounds, as well as high-level tasks such as strategic planning, currently require human expertise.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In many cases, the use of humans is more cost-effective than mechanical approaches even where the automation of industrial tasks is possible.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Therefore, algorithmic management as the digital rationalization of human labor instead of its substitution has emerged as an alternative technological strategy.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Overcoming these obstacles is a theorized path to post-scarcity economics.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] As of 2025-2026, real-world deployment of advanced robotics has revealed critical infrastructure limitations, such as "battery-life bottlenecks" (typically 2–4 hours of operation per charge) and the requirement for high-bandwidth Wi-Fi and specialized flooring for reliable function.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Additionally, robots continue to struggle with unpredictable human-made obstructions, which still necessitate human intervention to maintain operational flow.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Increased automation often causes workers to feel anxious about losing their jobs as technology renders their skills or experience unnecessary.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Early in the Industrial Revolution, when inventions like the steam engine were making some job categories expendable, workers forcefully resisted these changes.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Luddites, for instance, were English textile workers who protested the introduction of weaving machines by destroying them.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] More recently, some residents of Chandler, Arizona, have slashed tires and pelted rocks at a self-driving car, in protest over the cars' perceived threat to human safety and job prospects.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The relative anxiety about automation reflected in opinion polls seems to correlate closely with the strength of organized labor in that region or nation.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] According to one estimate, 47% of all current jobs in the US have the potential to be fully automated by 2033.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Furthermore, wages and educational attainment appear to be strongly negatively correlated with an occupation's risk of being automated.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Erik Brynjolfsson and Andrew McAfee argue that "there's never been a better time to be a worker with special skills or the right education, because these people can use technology to create and capture value.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Research by Carl Benedikt Frey and Michael Osborne of the Oxford Martin School argued that employees engaged in "tasks following well-defined procedures that can easily be performed by sophisticated algorithms" are at risk of displacement, and 47% of jobs in the US were at risk.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The study, released as a working paper in 2013 and published in 2017, predicted that automation would put low-paid physical occupations most at risk, by surveying a group of colleagues on their opinions.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] However, according to a study published in *McKinsey Quarterly* in 2015 the impact of computerization in most cases is not the replacement of employees but the automation of portions of the tasks they perform.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The methodology of the McKinsey study has been heavily criticized for being intransparent and relying on subjective assessments.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The methodology of Frey and Osborne has been subjected to criticism, as lacking evidence, historical awareness, or credible methodology.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Additionally, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) found that across the 21 OECD countries, 9% of jobs are automatable.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Based on a formula by Gilles Saint-Paul, an economist at Toulouse 1 University, the demand for unskilled human capital declines at a slower rate than the demand for skilled human capital increases.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In the long run and for society as a whole it has led to cheaper products, lower average work hours, and new industries forming (i.e., robotics industries, computer industries, design industries).
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] These new industries provide many high salary skill-based jobs to the economy.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] By 2030, between 3 and 14 percent of the global workforce will be forced to switch job categories due to automation eliminating jobs in an entire sector.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] While the number of jobs lost to automation is often offset by jobs gained from technological advances, the same type of job loss is not the same one replaced and that leading to increasing unemployment in the lower-middle class.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] This occurs largely in the US and developed countries where technological advances contribute to higher demand for highly skilled labor but demand for middle-wage labor continues to fall.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Economists call this trend "income polarization" where unskilled labor wages are driven down and skilled labor is driven up and it is predicted to continue in developed economies.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Lights-out manufacturing is a production system with no human workers, to eliminate labor costs.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] It grew in popularity in the U.S. when General Motors in 1982 implemented humans "hands-off" manufacturing to "replace risk-averse bureaucracy with automation and robots".
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] However, the factory never reached full "lights out" status.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The costs of automation to the environment are different depending on the technology, product or engine automated.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] There are automated engines that consume more energy resources from the Earth in comparison with previous engines and vice versa.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Hazardous operations, such as oil refining, the manufacturing of industrial chemicals, and all forms of metal working, were always early contenders for automation.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The automation of vehicles could prove to have a substantial impact on the environment, although the nature of this impact could be beneficial or harmful depending on several factors.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Because automated vehicles are much less likely to get into accidents compared to human-driven vehicles, some precautions built into current models (such as anti-lock brakes or laminated glass) would not be required for self-driving versions.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Removal of these safety features reduces the weight of the vehicle, and coupled with more precise acceleration and braking, as well as fuel-efficient route mapping, can increase fuel economy and reduce emissions.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Despite this, some researchers theorize that an increase in the production of self-driving cars could lead to a boom in vehicle ownership and usage, which could potentially negate any environmental benefits of self-driving cars if they are used more frequently.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Automation of homes and home appliances is also thought to impact the environment.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] This study, along with others, indicated that the smart home's ability to monitor and adjust consumption levels would reduce unnecessary energy usage.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] However, some research suggests that smart homes might not be as efficient as non-automated homes.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] A more recent study has indicated that, while monitoring and adjusting consumption levels do decrease unnecessary energy use, this process requires monitoring systems that also consume an amount of energy.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The energy required to run these systems sometimes negates their benefits, resulting in little to no ecological benefit.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Another major shift in automation is the increased demand for flexibility and convertibility in manufacturing processes.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Manufacturers are increasingly demanding the ability to easily switch from manufacturing Product A to manufacturing Product B without having to completely rebuild the production lines.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Flexibility and distributed processes have led to the introduction of Automated Guided Vehicles with Natural Features Navigation.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Former analog-based instrumentation was replaced by digital equivalents which can be more accurate and flexible, and offer greater scope for more sophisticated configuration, parametrization, and operation.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] This was accompanied by the fieldbus revolution which provided a networked (i.e. a single cable) means of communicating between control systems and field-level instrumentation, eliminating hard-wiring.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Discrete manufacturing plants adopted these technologies fast.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The more conservative process industries with their longer plant life cycles have been slower to adopt and analog-based measurement and control still dominate.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The growing use of Industrial Ethernet on the factory floor is pushing these trends still further, enabling manufacturing plants to be integrated more tightly within the enterprise, via the internet if necessary.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Global competition has also increased demand for Reconfigurable Manufacturing Systems.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Engineers can now have numerical control over automated devices.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The result has been a rapidly expanding range of applications and human activities.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Computer-aided technologies (or CAx) now serve as the basis for mathematical and organizational tools used to create complex systems.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Notable examples of CAx include computer-aided design (CAD software) and computer-aided manufacturing (CAM software).
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The improved design, analysis, and manufacture of products enabled by CAx has been beneficial for industry.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Information technology, together with industrial machinery and processes, can assist in the design, implementation, and monitoring of control systems.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] One example of an industrial control system is a programmable logic controller (PLC).
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] PLCs are specialized hardened computers which are frequently used to synchronize the flow of inputs from (physical) sensors and events with the flow of outputs to actuators and events.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Human-machine interfaces (HMI) or computer human interfaces (CHI), formerly known as *man-machine interfaces*, are usually employed to communicate with PLCs and other computers.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Service personnel who monitor and control through HMIs can be called by different names.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In the industrial process and manufacturing environments, they are called operators or something similar.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In boiler houses and central utility departments, they are called *stationary engineers*.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Host simulation software (HSS) is a commonly used testing tool that is used to test the equipment software.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] HSS is used to test equipment performance concerning factory automation standards (timeouts, response time, processing time).
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Cognitive automation, as a subset of AI, is an emerging genus of automation enabled by cognitive computing.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Its primary concern is the automation of clerical tasks and workflows that consist of structuring unstructured data.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Cognitive automation relies on multiple disciplines: natural language processing, real-time computing, machine learning algorithms, big data analytics, and evidence-based learning.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Artificially intelligent computer-aided design (CAD) can use text-to-3D, image-to-3D, and video-to-3D to automate in 3D modeling.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] AI CAD libraries could also be developed using linked open data of schematics and diagrams.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Ai CAD assistants are used as tools to help streamline workflow.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Technologies like solar panels, wind turbines, and other renewable energy sources—together with smart grids, micro-grids, battery storage—can automate power production.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Many agricultural operations are automated with machinery and equipment to improve their diagnosis, decision-making and/or performing.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Agricultural automation can relieve the drudgery of agricultural work, improve the timeliness and precision of agricultural operations, raise productivity and resource-use efficiency, build resilience, and improve food quality and safety.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Increased productivity can free up labour, allowing agricultural households to spend more time elsewhere.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has resulted in progressive shifts to digital equipment and robotics.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization has generally increased in recent years.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Many supermarkets and even smaller stores are rapidly introducing self-checkout systems reducing the need for employing checkout workers.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In the U.S., the retail industry employs 15.9 million people as of 2017 (around 1 in 9 Americans in the workforce).
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Globally, an estimated 192 million workers could be affected by automation according to research by Eurasia Group.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Online shopping could be considered a form of automated retail as the payment and checkout are through an automated online transaction processing system, with the share of online retail accounting jumping from 5.1% in 2011 to 8.3% in 2016.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] However, two-thirds of books, music, and films are now purchased online.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In addition, automation and online shopping could reduce demands for shopping malls, and retail property, which in the United States is currently estimated to account for 31% of all commercial property or around 7 billion square feet (650 million square metres).
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Amazon has gained much of the growth in recent years for online shopping, accounting for half of the growth in online retail in 2016.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Other forms of automation can also be an integral part of online shopping, for example, the deployment of automated warehouse robotics such as that applied by Amazon using Kiva Systems.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The food retail industry has started to apply automation to the ordering process; McDonald's has introduced touch screen ordering and payment systems in many of its restaurants, reducing the need for as many cashier employees.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The University of Texas at Austin has introduced fully automated cafe retail locations.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Some cafes and restaurants have utilized mobile and tablet "apps" to make the ordering process more efficient by customers ordering and paying on their device.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Some restaurants have automated food delivery to tables of customers using a conveyor belt system.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The use of robots is sometimes employed to replace waiting staff.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Automation in construction is the combination of methods, processes, and systems that allow for greater machine autonomy in construction activities.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Construction automation may have multiple goals, including but not limited to, reducing jobsite injuries, decreasing activity completion times, and assisting with quality control and quality assurance.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Automated mining involves the removal of human labor from the mining process.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The mining industry is currently in the transition towards automation.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Currently, it can still require a large amount of human capital, particularly in the third world where labor costs are low so there is less incentive for increasing efficiency through automation.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) started the research and development of automated visual surveillance and monitoring (VSAM) program, between 1997 and 1999, and airborne video surveillance (AVS) programs, from 1998 to 2002.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Currently, there is a major effort underway in the vision community to develop a fully-automated tracking surveillance system.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Automated video surveillance monitors people and vehicles in real-time within a busy environment.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Existing automated surveillance systems are based on the environment they are primarily designed to observe, i.e., indoor, outdoor or airborne, the number of sensors that the automated system can handle and the mobility of sensors, i.e., stationary camera vs. mobile camera.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The purpose of a surveillance system is to record properties and trajectories of objects in a given area, generate warnings or notify the designated authorities in case of occurrence of particular events.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] As demands for safety and mobility have grown and technological possibilities have multiplied, interest in automation has grown.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Seeking to accelerate the development and introduction of fully automated vehicles and highways, the U.S.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Congress authorized more than $650 million over six years for intelligent transport systems (ITS) and demonstration projects in the 1991 *Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act* (ISTEA).
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Full automation commonly defined as requiring no control or very limited control by the driver; such automation would be accomplished through a combination of sensor, computer, and communications systems in vehicles and along the roadway.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Fully automated driving would, in theory, allow closer vehicle spacing and higher speeds, which could enhance traffic capacity in places where additional road building is physically impossible, politically unacceptable, or prohibitively expensive.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Automated controls also might enhance road safety by reducing the opportunity for driver error, which causes a large share of motor vehicle crashes.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Other potential benefits include improved air quality (as a result of more-efficient traffic flows), increased fuel economy, and spin-off technologies generated during research and development related to automated highway systems.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Automated waste collection trucks prevent the need for as many workers as well as easing the level of labor required to provide the service.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Business process automation (BPA) is the technology-enabled automation of complex business processes.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] It can help to streamline a business for simplicity, achieve digital transformation, increase service quality, improve service delivery or contain costs.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] BPA consists of integrating applications, restructuring labor resources and using software applications throughout the organization.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Robotic process automation (RPA; or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0) is an emerging field within BPA and uses AI.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] BPAs can be implemented in a number of business areas including recruitment, marketing, sales and workflow.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Home automation (also called **domotics**) designates an emerging practice of increased automation of household appliances and features in residential dwellings, particularly through electronic means that allow for things impracticable, overly expensive or simply not possible in recent past decades.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The rise in the usage of home automation solutions has taken a turn reflecting the increased dependency of people on such automation solutions.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] However, the increased comfort that gets added through these automation solutions is remarkable.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Automation is essential for many scientific and clinical applications.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Therefore, automation has been extensively employed in laboratories.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] From as early as 1980 fully automated laboratories have already been working.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] However, automation has not become widespread in laboratories due to its high cost.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] This may change with the ability of integrating low-cost devices with standard laboratory equipment.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Autosamplers are common devices used in laboratory automation.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Logistics automation is the application of computer software or automated machinery to improve the efficiency of logistics operations.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Typically this refers to operations within a warehouse or distribution center, with broader tasks undertaken by supply chain engineering systems and enterprise resource planning systems.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Industrial automation deals primarily with the automation of manufacturing, quality control, and material handling processes.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] General-purpose controllers for industrial processes include programmable logic controllers, stand-alone I/O modules, and computers.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Industrial automation is to replace the human action and manual command-response activities with the use of mechanized equipment and logical programming commands.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] One trend is increased use of machine vision to provide automatic inspection and robot guidance functions, another is a continuing increase in the use of robots.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Industrial automation is simply required in industries.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The rise of industrial automation is directly tied to the "Fourth Industrial Revolution", which is better known now as Industry 4.0.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Originating from Germany, Industry 4.0 encompasses numerous devices, concepts, and machines, as well as the advancement of the industrial internet of things (IIoT).
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] An "Internet of Things is a seamless integration of diverse physical objects in the Internet through a virtual representation".
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] These new advancements have drawn attention to the world of automation and have shown ways for it to increase productivity and efficiency in machinery and manufacturing facilities.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 works with the IIoT and software/hardware to connect in a way that (through communication technologies) add enhancements and improve manufacturing processes.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Being able to create more advanced manufacturing is now possible with these new technologies.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] It opens up an improved manufacturing platform.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Implementation of systems such as SCADA is an example of software that takes place in industrial automation today.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] SCADA is a supervisory data collection software, just one of the many used in industrial automation.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 covers many areas in manufacturing.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Industrial robotics is a sub-branch in industrial automation that aids in various manufacturing processes.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Such manufacturing processes include machining, welding, painting, assembling and material handling to name a few.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Industrial robots use various mechanical, electrical as well as software systems to allow for high precision, accuracy and speed that far exceed any human performance.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The birth of industrial robots came shortly after World War II as the U.S. saw the need for a quicker way to produce industrial and consumer goods.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Servos, digital logic and solid-state electronics allowed engineers to build better and faster systems and over time these systems were improved and revised to the point where a single robot is capable of running 24 hours a day with little or no maintenance.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] In 1997, there were 700,000 industrial robots in use, the number has risen to 1.8M in 2017 In recent years, AI with robotics is also used in creating an automatic labeling solution, using robotic arms as the automatic label applicator, and AI for learning and detecting the products to be labelled.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Industrial automation incorporates programmable logic controllers in the manufacturing process.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) use a processing system which allows for variation of controls of inputs and outputs using simple programming.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] PLCs make use of programmable memory, storing instructions and functions like logic, sequencing, timing, counting, etc.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Using a logic-based language, a PLC can receive a variety of inputs and return a variety of logical outputs, the input devices being sensors and output devices being motors, valves, etc.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] PLCs are similar to computers, however, while computers are optimized for calculations, PLCs are optimized for control tasks and use in industrial environments.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] They are built so that only basic logic-based programming knowledge is needed and to handle vibrations, high temperatures, humidity, and noise.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The greatest advantage PLCs offer is their flexibility.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] With the same basic controllers, a PLC can operate a range of different control systems.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] PLCs make it unnecessary to rewire a system to change the control system.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] This flexibility leads to a cost-effective system for complex and varied control systems.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] PLCs can range from small "building brick" devices with tens of I/O in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs (I/O), extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] It was from the automotive industry in the United States that the PLC was born.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Before the PLC, control, sequencing, and safety interlock logic for manufacturing automobiles was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Since these could number in the hundreds or even thousands, the process for updating such facilities for the yearly model change-over was very time-consuming and expensive, as electricians needed to individually rewire the relays to change their operational characteristics.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] When digital computers became available, being general-purpose programmable devices, they were soon applied to control sequential and combinatorial logic in industrial processes.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] However, these early computers required specialist programmers and stringent operating environmental control for temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] To meet these challenges, the PLC was developed with several key attributes.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] It would tolerate the shop-floor environment, it would support discrete (bit-form) input and output in an easily extensible manner, it would not require years of training to use, and it would permit its operation to be monitored.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Since many industrial processes have timescales easily addressed by millisecond response times, modern (fast, small, reliable) electronics greatly facilitate building reliable controllers, and performance could be traded off for reliability.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Agent-assisted automation refers to automation used by call center agents to handle customer inquiries.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The key benefit of agent-assisted automation is compliance and error-proofing.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] Agents are sometimes not fully trained or they forget or ignore key steps in the process.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] The use of automation ensures that what is supposed to happen on the call actually does, every time.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p01] There are two basic types: desktop automation and automated voice solutions.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] One of the simplest types of control is *on-off* control.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] An example is a thermostat used on household appliances which either open or close an electrical contact.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Sequence control, in which a programmed sequence of *discrete* operations is performed, often based on system logic that involves system states.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] An elevator control system is an example of sequence control.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] A proportional–integral–derivative controller (PID controller) is a control loop feedback mechanism (controller) widely used in industrial control systems.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] The theoretical understanding and application date from the 1920s, and they are implemented in nearly all analog control systems; originally in mechanical controllers, and then using discrete electronics and latterly in industrial process computers.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Sequential control may be either to a fixed sequence or to a logical one that will perform different actions depending on various system states.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] An example of an adjustable but otherwise fixed sequence is a timer on a lawn sprinkler.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] States refer to the various conditions that can occur in a use or sequence scenario of the system.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] An example is an elevator, which uses logic based on the system state to perform certain actions in response to its state and operator input.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] For example, if the operator presses the floor n button, the system will respond depending on whether the elevator is stopped or moving, going up or down, or if the door is open or closed, and other conditions.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Early development of sequential control was relay logic, by which electrical relays engage electrical contacts which either start or interrupt power to a device.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Relays were first used in telegraph networks before being developed for controlling other devices, such as when starting and stopping industrial-sized electric motors or opening and closing solenoid valves.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Using relays for control purposes allowed event-driven control, where actions could be triggered out of sequence, in response to external events.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] These were more flexible in their response than the rigid single-sequence cam timers.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] More complicated examples involved maintaining safe sequences for devices such as swing bridge controls, where a lock bolt needed to be disengaged before the bridge could be moved, and the lock bolt could not be released until the safety gates had already been closed.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] The total number of relays and cam timers can number into the hundreds or even thousands in some factories.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Early programming techniques and languages were needed to make such systems manageable, one of the first being ladder logic, where diagrams of the interconnected relays resembled the rungs of a ladder.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Special computers called programmable logic controllers were later designed to replace these collections of hardware with a single, more easily re-programmed unit.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] In a typical hard-wired motor start and stop circuit (called a *control circuit*) a motor is started by pushing a "Start" or "Run" button that activates a pair of electrical relays.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] The "lock-in" relay locks in contacts that keep the control circuit energized when the push-button is released.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] (The start button is a normally open contact and the stop button is a normally closed contact.) Another relay energizes a switch that powers the device that throws the motor starter switch (three sets of contacts for three-phase industrial power) in the main power circuit.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Large motors use high voltage and experience high in-rush current, making speed important in making and breaking contact.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] This can be dangerous for personnel and property with manual switches.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] The "lock-in" contacts in the start circuit and the main power contacts for the motor are held engaged by their respective electromagnets until a "stop" or "off" button is pressed, which de-energizes the lock in relay.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Commonly interlocks are added to a control circuit.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Suppose that the motor in the example is powering machinery that has a critical need for lubrication.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] In this case, an interlock could be added to ensure that the oil pump is running before the motor starts.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Timers, limit switches, and electric eyes are other common elements in control circuits.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Solenoid valves are widely used on compressed air or hydraulic fluid for powering actuators on mechanical components.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Computers can perform both sequential control and feedback control, and typically a single computer will do both in an industrial application.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) are a type of special-purpose microprocessor that replaced many hardware components such as timers and drum sequencers used in relay logic–type systems.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] General-purpose process control computers have increasingly replaced stand-alone controllers, with a single computer able to perform the operations of hundreds of controllers.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Process control computers can process data from a network of PLCs, instruments, and controllers to implement typical (such as PID) control of many individual variables or, in some cases, to implement complex control algorithms using multiple inputs and mathematical manipulations.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] They can also analyze data and create real-time graphical displays for operators and run reports for operators, engineers, and management.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Control of an automated teller machine (ATM) is an example of an interactive process in which a computer will perform a logic-derived response to a user selection based on information retrieved from a networked database.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] The ATM process has similarities with other online transaction processes.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] The different logical responses are called *scenarios*.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] Such processes are typically designed with the aid of use cases and flowcharts, which guide the writing of the software code.
[src:plc-scada/automation-p02] The earliest feedback control mechanism was the water clock invented by Greek engineer Ctesibius (285–222 BC).
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] A **distributed control system** (**DCS**) is a computerized control system for a process or plant usually with many control loops, in which autonomous controllers are distributed throughout the system, but there is no central operator supervisory control.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] This is in contrast to systems that use centralized controllers; either discrete controllers located at a central control room or within a central computer.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The DCS concept increases reliability and reduces installation costs by localizing control functions near the process plant, with remote monitoring and supervision.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Distributed control systems first emerged in large, high value, safety critical process industries, and were attractive because the DCS manufacturer would supply both the local control level and central supervisory equipment as an integrated package, thus reducing design integration risk.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Today the functionality of Supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) and DCS systems are very similar, but DCS tends to be used on large continuous process plants where high reliability and security is important, and the control room is not necessarily geographically remote.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Many machine control systems exhibit similar properties as plant and process control systems do.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The key attribute of a DCS is its reliability due to the distribution of the control processing around nodes in the system.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] This mitigates a single processor failure.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] If a processor fails, it will only affect one section of the plant process, as opposed to a failure of a central computer which would affect the whole process.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] This distribution of computing power local to the field Input/Output (I/O) connection racks also ensures fast controller processing times by removing possible network and central processing delays.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The accompanying diagram is a general model which shows functional manufacturing levels using computerised control.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Levels 1 and 2 are the functional levels of a traditional DCS, in which all equipment are part of an integrated system from a single manufacturer.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Levels 3 and 4 are not strictly process control in the traditional sense, but where production control and scheduling takes place.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The processor nodes and operator graphical displays are connected over proprietary or industry standard networks, and network reliability is increased by dual redundancy cabling over diverse routes.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] This distributed topology also reduces the amount of field cabling by siting the I/O modules and their associated processors close to the process plant.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The processors receive information from input modules, process the information and decide control actions to be signalled by the output modules.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The field inputs and outputs can be analog signals e.g.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] 4–20 mA DC current loop or two-state signals that switch either "on" or "off", such as relay contacts or a semiconductor switch.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] DCSs are connected to sensors and actuators and use setpoint control to control the flow of material through the plant.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] A typical application is a PID controller fed by a flow meter and using a control valve as the final control element.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The DCS sends the setpoint required by the process to the controller which instructs a valve to operate so that the process reaches and stays at the desired setpoint.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Large oil refineries and chemical plants have several thousand I/O points and employ very large DCS.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Processes are not limited to fluidic flow through pipes, however, and can also include things like paper machines and their associated quality controls, variable speed drives and motor control centers, cement kilns, mining operations, ore processing facilities, and many others.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] DCSs in very high reliability applications can have dual redundant processors with "hot" switch over on fault, to enhance the reliability of the control system.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Although 4–20 mA has been the main field signalling standard, modern DCS systems can also support fieldbus digital protocols, such as Foundation Fieldbus, profibus, HART, modbus, PC Link, etc.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Modern DCSs also support neural networks and fuzzy logic applications.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Recent research focuses on the synthesis of optimal distributed controllers, which optimizes a certain H-infinity or the H 2 control criterion.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Distributed control systems (DCS) are dedicated systems used in manufacturing processes that are continuous or batch-oriented.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Initially, control would be from panels local to the process plant.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] However this required a large amount of human oversight to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently-staffed central control room.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Effectively this was the centralisation of all the localised panels, with the advantages of lower manning levels and easier overview of the process.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Often the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were transmitted back to plant.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, and continual operator movement within the control room was required to view different parts of the process.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] With the coming of electronic processors and graphic displays it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] These could be distributed around plant, and communicate with the graphic display in the control room or rooms.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The distributed control system was born.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The introduction of DCSs allowed easy interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Early minicomputers were used in the control of industrial processes since the beginning of the 1960s.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The IBM 1800, for example, was an early computer that had input/output hardware to gather process signals in a plant for conversion from field contact levels (for digital points) and analog signals to the digital domain.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The first industrial control computer system was built 1959 at the Texaco Port Arthur, Texas, refinery with an RW-300 of the Ramo-Wooldridge Company.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] In 1975, both HONEYWELL and Japanese electrical engineering firm Yokogawa introduced their own independently produced DCS's - TDC 2000 and CENTUM systems, respectively.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] US-based Bristol also introduced their UCS 3000 universal controller in 1975.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] In 1978 Valmet introduced their own DCS system called Damatic (latest web-based generation Valmet DNAe).
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] In 1980, Bailey (now part of ABB) introduced the NETWORK 90 system, Fisher Controls (now part of Emerson Electric) introduced the PROVoX system, Fischer & Porter Company (now also part of ABB) introduced DCI-4000 (DCI stands for Distributed Control Instrumentation).
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The DCS largely came about due to the increased availability of microcomputers and the proliferation of microprocessors in the world of process control.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Computers had already been applied to process automation for some time in the form of both direct digital control (DDC) and setpoint control.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] In the early 1970s Taylor Instrument Company, (now part of ABB) developed the 1010 system, Foxboro the FOX1 system, Fisher Controls the DC2 system and Bailey Controls the 1055 systems.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] All of these were DDC applications implemented within minicomputers (DEC PDP-11, Varian Data Machines, MODCOMP etc.) and connected to proprietary Input/Output hardware.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Sophisticated (for the time) continuous as well as batch control was implemented in this way.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] A more conservative approach was setpoint control, where process computers supervised clusters of analog process controllers.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] A workstation provided visibility into the process using text and crude character graphics.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Availability of a fully functional graphical user interface was a way away.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Central to the DCS model was the inclusion of control function blocks.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Function blocks evolved from early, more primitive DDC concepts of "Table Driven" software.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] One of the first embodiments of object-oriented software, function blocks were self-contained "blocks" of code that emulated analog hardware control components and performed tasks that were essential to process control, such as execution of PID algorithms.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Function blocks continue to endure as the predominant method of control for DCS suppliers, and are supported by key technologies such as Foundation Fieldbus today.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Midac Systems, of Sydney, Australia, developed an objected-oriented distributed direct digital control system in 1982.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The central system ran 11 microprocessors sharing tasks and common memory and connected to a serial communication network of distributed controllers each running two Z80s.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The system was installed at the University of Melbourne.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Digital communication between distributed controllers, workstations and other computing elements (peer to peer access) was one of the primary advantages of the DCS.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Attention was duly focused on the networks, which provided the all-important lines of communication that, for process applications, had to incorporate specific functions such as determinism and redundancy.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] As a result, many suppliers embraced the IEEE 802.4 networking standard.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] This decision set the stage for the wave of migrations necessary when information technology moved into process automation and IEEE 802.3 rather than IEEE 802.4 prevailed as the control LAN.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] In the 1980s, users began to look at DCSs as more than just basic process control.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] A very early example of a Direct Digital Control DCS was completed by the Australian business Midac in 1981–82 using R-Tec Australian designed hardware.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The system installed at the University of Melbourne used a serial communications network, connecting campus buildings back to a control room "front end".
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Each remote unit ran two Z80 microprocessors, while the front end ran eleven Z80s in a parallel processing configuration with paged common memory to share tasks and that could run up to 20,000 concurrent control objects.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] It was believed that if openness could be achieved and greater amounts of data could be shared throughout the enterprise that even greater things could be achieved.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The first attempts to increase the openness of DCSs resulted in the adoption of the predominant operating system of the day: *UNIX*.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] UNIX and its companion networking technology TCP-IP were developed by the US Department of Defense for openness, which was precisely the issue the process industries were looking to resolve.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] As a result, suppliers also began to adopt Ethernet-based networks with their own proprietary protocol layers.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The full TCP/IP standard was not implemented, but the use of Ethernet made it possible to implement the first instances of object management and global data access technology.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The 1980s also witnessed the first PLCs integrated into the DCS infrastructure.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Plant-wide historians also emerged to capitalize on the extended reach of automation systems.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The first DCS supplier to adopt UNIX and Ethernet networking technologies was Foxboro, who introduced the I/A Series system in 1987.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The drive toward openness in the 1980s gained momentum through the 1990s with the increased adoption of commercial off-the-shelf (COTS) components and IT standards.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Probably the biggest transition undertaken during this time was the move from the UNIX operating system to the Windows environment.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] While the realm of the real time operating system (RTOS) for control applications remains dominated by real time commercial variants of UNIX or proprietary operating systems, everything above real-time control has made the transition to Windows.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The introduction of Microsoft at the desktop and server layers resulted in the development of technologies such as OLE for process control (OPC), which is now a de facto industry connectivity standard.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Internet technology also began to make its mark in automation and the world, with most DCS HMI supporting Internet connectivity.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The 1990s were also known for the "Fieldbus Wars", where rival organizations competed to define what would become the IEC fieldbus standard for digital communication with field instrumentation instead of 4–20 milliamp analog communications.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The first fieldbus installations occurred in the 1990s.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Towards the end of the decade, the technology began to develop significant momentum, with the market consolidated around Ethernet I/P, Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA for process automation applications.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Fieldbus technics have been used to integrate machine, drives, quality and condition monitoring applications to one DCS with Valmet DNA system.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The impact of COTS, however, was most pronounced at the hardware layer.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] For years, the primary business of DCS suppliers had been the supply of large amounts of hardware, particularly I/O and controllers.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The initial proliferation of DCSs required the installation of prodigious amounts of this hardware, most of it manufactured from the bottom up by DCS suppliers.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Standard computer components from manufacturers such as Intel and Motorola, however, made it cost prohibitive for DCS suppliers to continue making their own components, workstations, and networking hardware.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] As the suppliers made the transition to COTS components, they also discovered that the hardware market was shrinking fast.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] COTS not only resulted in lower manufacturing costs for the supplier, but also steadily decreasing prices for the end users, who were also becoming increasingly vocal over what they perceived to be unduly high hardware costs.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The traditional DCS suppliers introduced new generation DCS System based on the latest Communication and IEC Standards, which resulting in a trend of combining the traditional concepts/functionalities for PLC and DCS into a one for all solution—named "Process Automation System" (PAS).
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The gaps among the various systems remain at the areas such as: the database integrity, pre-engineering functionality, system maturity, communication transparency and reliability.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] While it is expected the cost ratio is relatively the same (the more powerful the systems are, the more expensive they will be), the reality of the automation business is often operating strategically case by case.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The current next evolution step is called Collaborative Process Automation Systems.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] To compound the issue, suppliers were also realizing that the hardware market was becoming saturated.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The life cycle of hardware components such as I/O and wiring is also typically in the range of 15 to over 20 years, making for a challenging replacement market.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Many of the older systems that were installed in the 1970s and 1980s are still in use today, and there is a considerable installed base of systems in the market that are approaching the end of their useful life.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Developed industrial economies in North America, Europe, and Japan already had many thousands of DCSs installed, and with few if any new plants being built, the market for new hardware was shifting rapidly to smaller, albeit faster growing regions such as China, Latin America, and Eastern Europe.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Because of the shrinking hardware business, suppliers began to make the challenging transition from a hardware-based business model to one based on software and value-added services.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] It is a transition that is still being made today.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The applications portfolio offered by suppliers expanded considerably in the '90s to include areas such as production management, model-based control, real-time optimization, plant asset management (PAM), Real-time performance management (RPM) tools, alarm management, and many others.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] To obtain the true value from these applications, however, often requires a considerable service content, which the suppliers also provide.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Increasingly, and ironically, DCS are becoming centralised at plant level, with the ability to log into the remote equipment.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] This enables operator to control both at enterprise level ( macro ) and at the equipment level (micro), both within and outside the plant, because the importance of the physical location drops due to interconnectivity primarily thanks to wireless and remote access.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] The more wireless protocols are developed and refined, the more they are included in DCS.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] DCS controllers are now often equipped with embedded servers and provide on-the-go web access.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Whether DCS will lead Industrial Internet of Things (IIOT) or borrow key elements from remains to be seen.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] Many vendors provide the option of a mobile HMI, ready for both Android and iOS.
[src:plc-scada/distributed-control-system] With these interfaces, the threat of security breaches and possible damage to plant and process are now very real.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] In the industrial design field of human–computer interaction, a **user interface** (**UI**) is the space where interactions between humans and machines occur.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The goal of this interaction is to allow effective operation and control of the machine from the human end, while the machine simultaneously feeds back information that aids the operators' decision-making process.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Examples of this broad concept of user interfaces include the interactive aspects of computer operating systems, hand tools, heavy machinery operator controls and process controls.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The design considerations applicable when creating user interfaces are related to, or involve such disciplines as, ergonomics and psychology.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Generally, the goal of user interface design is to produce a user interface that makes it easy, efficient, and enjoyable (user-friendly) to operate a machine in the way which produces the desired result (i.e. maximum usability).
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] This generally means that the operator needs to provide minimal input to achieve the desired output, and also that the machine minimizes undesired outputs to the user.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] User interfaces are composed of one or more layers, including a **human–machine interface** (**HMI**) that typically interfaces machines with physical input hardware (such as keyboards, mice, or game pads) and output hardware (such as computer monitors, speakers, and printers).
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] A device that implements an HMI is called a human interface device (HID).
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] User interfaces that dispense with the physical movement of body parts as an intermediary step between the brain and the machine use no input or output devices except electrodes alone; they are called brain–computer interfaces (BCIs) or brain–machine interfaces (BMIs).
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Other terms for human–machine interfaces are **man–machine interface** (**MMI**) and, when the machine in question is a computer, **human–computer interface**.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Additional UI layers may interact with one or more human senses, including: tactile UI (touch), visual UI (sight), auditory UI (sound), olfactory UI (smell), equilibria UI (balance), and gustatory UI (taste).
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The user interface or *human–machine interface* is the part of the machine that handles the human–machine interaction.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Membrane switches, rubber keypads and touchscreens are examples of the physical part of the Human Machine Interface which we can see and touch.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] In complex systems, the human–machine interface is typically computerized.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The term *human–computer interface* refers to this kind of system.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] In the context of computing, the term typically extends as well to the software dedicated to control the physical elements used for human–computer interaction.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The engineering of human–machine interfaces is enhanced by considering ergonomics (human factors).
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The corresponding disciplines are human factors engineering (HFE) and usability engineering (UE) which is part of systems engineering.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Tools used for incorporating human factors in the interface design are developed based on knowledge of computer science, such as computer graphics, operating systems, programming languages.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Nowadays, we use the expression graphical user interface for human–machine interface on computers, as nearly all of them are now using graphics.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Multimodal interfaces allow users to interact using more than one modality of user input.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] There is a difference between a user interface and an operator interface or a human–machine interface (HMI).
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] In science fiction, HMI is sometimes used to refer to what is better described as a direct neural interface.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] However, this latter usage is seeing increasing application in the real-life use of (medical) prostheses—the artificial extension that replaces a missing body part (e.g., cochlear implants).
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] In some circumstances, computers might observe the user and react according to their actions without specific commands.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] A means of tracking parts of the body is required, and sensors noting the position of the head, direction of gaze and so on have been used experimentally.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] This is particularly relevant to immersive interfaces.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] In the batch era, computing power was extremely scarce and expensive.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Users had to accommodate computers rather than the other way around; user interfaces were considered overhead, and software was designed to keep the processor at maximum utilization with as little overhead as possible.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The input side of the user interfaces for batch machines was mainly punched cards or equivalent media like paper tape.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The output side added line printers to these media.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] With the limited exception of the system operator's console, human beings did not interact with batch machines in real time at all.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Submitting a job to a batch machine involved first preparing a deck of punched cards that described a program and its dataset.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The program cards were not punched on the computer itself but on keypunches, specialized, typewriter-like machines that were notoriously bulky, unforgiving, and prone to mechanical failure.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The software interface was similarly unforgiving, with very strict syntaxes designed to be parsed by the smallest possible compilers and interpreters.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Once the cards were punched, one would drop them in a job queue and wait.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Eventually, operators would feed the deck to the computer, perhaps mounting magnetic tapes to supply another dataset or helper software.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The job would generate a printout, containing final results or an abort notice with an attached error log.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Successful runs might also write a result on magnetic tape or generate some data cards to be used in a later computation.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The turnaround time for a single job often spanned entire days.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] If one was very lucky, it might be hours; there was no real-time response.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] But there were worse fates than the card queue; some computers required an even more tedious and error-prone process of toggling in programs in binary code using console switches.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The very earliest machines had to be partly rewired to incorporate program logic into themselves, using devices known as plugboards.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Early batch systems gave the currently running job the entire computer; program decks and tapes had to include what we would now think of as operating system code to talk to I/O devices and do whatever other housekeeping was needed.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Midway through the batch period, after 1957, various groups began to experiment with so-called "load-and-go" systems.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] These used a monitor program which was always resident on the computer.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Programs could call the monitor for services.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Another function of the monitor was to do better error checking on submitted jobs, catching errors earlier and more intelligently and generating more useful feedback to the users.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Thus, monitors represented the first step towards both operating systems and explicitly designed user interfaces.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The earliest command-line systems combined teleprinters with computers, adapting a mature technology that had proven effective for mediating the transfer of information over wires between human beings.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Teleprinters had originally been invented as devices for automatic telegraph transmission and reception; they had a history going back to 1902 and had already become well-established in newsrooms and elsewhere by 1920.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] In reusing them, economy was certainly a consideration, but psychology and the rule of least surprise mattered as well; teleprinters provided a point of interface with the system that was familiar to many engineers and users.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The widespread adoption of video-display terminals (VDTs) in the mid-1970s ushered in the second phase of command-line systems.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] These cut latency further, because characters could be thrown on the phosphor dots of a screen more quickly than a printer head or carriage can move.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] They helped quell conservative resistance to interactive programming by cutting ink and paper consumables out of the cost picture, and were to the first TV generation of the late 1950s and 60s even more iconic and comfortable than teleprinters had been to the computer pioneers of the 1940s.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Just as importantly, the existence of an accessible screen—a two-dimensional display of text that could be rapidly and reversibly modified—made it economical for software designers to deploy interfaces that could be described as visual rather than textual.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The pioneering applications of this kind were computer games and text editors; close descendants of some of the earliest specimens, such as rogue(6), and vi(1), are still a live part of Unix tradition.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] In 1985, with the beginning of Microsoft Windows and other graphical user interfaces, IBM created what is called the Systems Application Architecture (SAA) standard which include the Common User Access (CUA) derivative.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] CUA successfully created what we know and use today in Windows, and most of the more recent MS-DOS or Windows Console Applications will use that standard as well.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] This defined that a pulldown menu system should be at the top of the screen, status bar at the bottom, shortcut keys should stay the same for all common functionality (F2 to Open for example would work in all applications that followed the SAA standard).
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] This greatly helped the speed at which users could learn an application so it caught on quick and became an industry standard.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Primary methods used in the interface design include prototyping and simulation.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] In broad terms, interfaces generally regarded as user friendly, efficient, intuitive, etc. are typified by one or more particular qualities.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Familiarity: Even if someone uses an interface for the first time, certain elements can still be familiar.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Real-life metaphors can be used to communicate meaning.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Responsiveness: A good interface should not feel sluggish.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] This means that the interface should provide good feedback to the user about what's happening and whether the user's input is being successfully processed.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Consistency: Keeping your interface consistent across your application is important because it allows users to recognize usage patterns.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Aesthetics: While you do not need to make an interface attractive for it to do its job, making something look good will make the time your users spend using your application more enjoyable; and happier users can only be a good thing.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Efficiency: Time is money, and a great interface should make the user more productive through shortcuts and good design.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Forgiveness: A good interface should not punish users for their mistakes but should instead provide the means to remedy them.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The principle of least astonishment (POLA) is a general principle in the design of all kinds of interfaces.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] It is based on the idea that human beings can only pay full attention to one thing at one time, leading to the conclusion that novelty should be minimized.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] If an interface is used persistently, the user will unavoidably develop habits for using the interface.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The designer's role can thus be characterized as ensuring the user forms good habits.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] If the designer is experienced with other interfaces, they will similarly develop habits, and often make unconscious assumptions regarding how the user will interact with the interface.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Peter Morville of Google designed the User Experience Honeycomb framework in 2004 when leading operations in user interface design.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The framework was created to guide user interface design.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] It would act as a guideline for many web development students for a decade.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Useful: Does the application fulfill a need?
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] A business's product or service needs to be useful.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Desirable: Is the design of the application sleek and to the point?
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The aesthetics of the system should be attractive, and easy to translate.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Findable: Are users able to quickly find the information they are looking for?
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Information needs to be findable and simple to navigate.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] A user should never have to hunt for your product or information.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Accessible: Does the application support enlarged text without breaking the framework?
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] An application should be accessible to those with disabilities.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Credible: Does the application exhibit trustworthy security and company details?
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] An application should be transparent, secure, and honest.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Valuable: Does the end-user think it's valuable?
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] If all 6 criteria are met, the end-user will find value and trust in the application.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Batch interfaces* are non-interactive user interfaces, where the user specifies all the details of the *batch job* in advance to batch processing, and receives the output when all the processing is done.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The computer does not prompt for further input after the processing has started.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Command line interfaces* (CLIs) prompt the user to provide input by typing a command string with the computer keyboard and respond by outputting text to the computer monitor.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Used by programmers and system administrators, in engineering and scientific environments, and by technically advanced personal computer users.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Conversational interfaces* enable users to command the computer with plain text English (e.g., via text messages, or chatbots) or voice commands, instead of graphic elements.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] These interfaces often emulate human-to-human conversations.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Conversational interface agents* attempt to personify the computer interface in the form of an animated person, robot, or other character (such as Microsoft's Clippy the paperclip), and present interactions in a conversational form.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Crossing-based interfaces* are graphical user interfaces in which the primary task consists in crossing boundaries instead of pointing.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Direct manipulation interface* is a general class of user interfaces that allow users to manipulate objects presented to them, using actions that correspond to the physical world, at least loosely.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Gesture interfaces* are graphical user interfaces which accept input in a form of hand gestures, or mouse gestures sketched with a computer mouse or a stylus.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Graphical user interfaces* (GUI) accept input via devices such as a computer keyboard and mouse and provide articulated graphical output on the computer monitor.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] There are at least two different principles widely used in GUI design: Object-oriented user interfaces (OOUIs) and application-oriented interfaces.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Hardware interfaces* are the physical, spatial interfaces found on products in the real world from toasters, to car dashboards, to airplane cockpits.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] They are generally a mixture of knobs, buttons, sliders, switches, and touchscreens.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Holographic user interfaces* provide input to electronic or electro-mechanical devices by passing a finger through reproduced holographic images of what would otherwise be tactile controls of those devices, floating freely in the air, detected by a wave source and without tactile interaction.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Intelligent user interfaces* are human–machine interfaces that aim to improve the efficiency, effectiveness, and naturalness of human–machine interaction by representing, reasoning, and acting on models of the user, domain, task, discourse, and media (e.g., graphics, natural language, gesture).
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Motion tracking interfaces* monitor the user's body motions and translate them into commands, some techniques of which were at one point patented by Apple.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Multi-screen interfaces*, employ multiple displays to provide a more flexible interaction.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] This is often employed in computer game interaction in both the commercial arcades and more recently the handheld markets.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Natural-language interfaces* are used for search engines and on webpages.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] User types in a question and waits for a response.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Non-command user interfaces*, which observe the user to infer their needs and intentions, without requiring that they formulate explicit commands.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Object-oriented user interfaces (OOUI)* are based on object-oriented programming metaphors, allowing users to manipulate simulated objects and their properties.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Permission-driven user interfaces* show or conceal menu options or functions depending on the user's level of permissions.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The system is intended to improve the user experience by removing items that are unavailable to the user.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] A user who sees functions that are unavailable for use may become frustrated.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] It also provides an enhancement to security by hiding functional items from unauthorized persons.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Reflexive user interfaces* where the users control and redefine the entire system via the user interface alone, for instance to change its command verbs.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Typically, this is only possible with very rich graphic user interfaces.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Search interface* is how the search box of a site is displayed, as well as the visual representation of the search results.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Tangible user interfaces*, which place a greater emphasis on touch and physical environment or its element.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Task-focused interfaces* are user interfaces which address the information overload problem of the desktop metaphor by making tasks, not files, the primary unit of interaction.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Text-based user interfaces* (TUIs) are user interfaces which interact via text.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] TUIs include command-line interfaces and text-based WIMP environments.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Touchscreens* are displays that accept input by touch of fingers or a stylus.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] Used in a growing amount of mobile devices and many types of point of sale, industrial processes and machines, self-service machines, etc.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Touch user interface* are graphical user interfaces using a touchpad or touchscreen display as a combined input and output device.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] They supplement or replace other forms of output with haptic feedback methods.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Voice user interfaces*, which accept input and provide output by generating voice prompts.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] The user input is made by pressing keys or buttons, or responding verbally to the interface.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Zero-input interfaces* get inputs from a set of sensors instead of querying the user with input dialogs.
[src:plc-scada/human-machine-interface] *Zooming user interfaces* are graphical user interfaces in which information objects are represented at different levels of scale and detail, and where the user can change the scale of the viewed area in order to show more detail.
[src:plc-scada/iec-61131-3] Part 3 of *IEC 61131* deals with basic software architecture and programming languages of the control program within PLC.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] An **industrial control system** (**ICS**) is an electronic control system and associated instrumentation used for industrial process control.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Control systems can range in size from a few modular panel-mounted controllers to large interconnected and interactive distributed control systems (DCSs) with many thousands of field connections.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Control systems receive data from remote sensors measuring process variables (PVs), compare the collected data with desired setpoints (SPs), and derive command functions that are used to control a process through the final control elements (FCEs), such as control valves.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Larger systems are usually implemented by supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) systems, or DCSs, and programmable logic controllers (PLCs), though SCADA and PLC systems are scalable down to small systems with few control loops.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Such systems are extensively used in industries such as chemical processing, pulp and paper manufacture, power generation, oil and gas processing, and telecommunications.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The simplest control systems are based around small discrete controllers with a single control loop each.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] These are usually panel mounted, which allows direct viewing of the front panel and provides a means of manual intervention by the operator, either to manually control the process or to change control setpoints.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Originally, these would be pneumatic controllers, a few of which are still in use, but nearly all are now electronic.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Quite complex systems can be created with networks of these controllers communicating using industry-standard protocols.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Networking allows the use of local or remote SCADA operator interfaces and enables the cascading and interlocking of controllers.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] However, as the number of control loops increases for a system design, there is a point where the use of a programmable logic controller (PLC) or distributed control system (DCS) is more manageable or cost-effective.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] A distributed control system (DCS) is a digital process control system (PCS) for a process or plant, wherein controller functions and field connection modules are distributed throughout the system.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] As the number of control loops grows, DCS becomes more cost effective than discrete controllers.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Additionally, a DCS provides supervisory viewing and management over large industrial processes.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] In a DCS, a hierarchy of controllers is connected by communication networks, allowing centralized control rooms and local on-plant monitoring and control.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] A DCS enables easy configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other computer systems such as production control.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] It also enables more sophisticated alarm handling, introduces automatic event logging, removes the need for physical records such as chart recorders and allows the control equipment to be networked and thereby located locally to the equipment being controlled to reduce cabling.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] A DCS typically uses custom-designed processors as controllers and uses either proprietary interconnections or standard protocols for communication.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Input and output modules form the peripheral components of the system.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The processors receive information from input modules, process the information and decide control actions to be performed by the output modules.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The input modules receive information from sensing instruments in the process (or field) and the output modules transmit instructions to the final control elements, such as control valves.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The field inputs and outputs can either be continuously changing analog signals, e.g., current loop or 2-state signals that switch either *on* or *off*, such as relay contacts or a semiconductor switch.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Distributed control systems can normally also support Foundation Fieldbus, PROFIBUS, HART, Modbus and other digital communication buses that carry not only input and output signals but also advanced messages such as error diagnostics and status signals.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) is a control system architecture that uses computers, networked data communications and graphical user interfaces for high-level process supervisory management.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA supervisory computer system.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] However, the real-time control logic or controller calculations are performed by networked modules which connect to other peripheral devices such as programmable logic controllers and discrete PID controllers which interface to the process plant or machinery.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The SCADA concept was developed as a universal means of remote access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers, allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become very similar to distributed control systems in function, but using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] They can control large-scale processes that can include multiple sites and work over large distances.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] This is a commonly used architecture industrial control systems, however there are concerns about SCADA systems being vulnerable to cyberwarfare or cyberterrorism attacks.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The SCADA software operates on a supervisory level as control actions are performed automatically by RTUs or PLCs.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] SCADA control functions are usually restricted to basic overriding or supervisory level intervention.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] A feedback control loop is directly controlled by the RTU or PLC, but the SCADA software monitors the overall performance of the loop.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] For example, a PLC may control the flow of cooling water through part of an industrial process to a set point level, but the SCADA system software will allow operators to change the set points for the flow.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The SCADA also enables alarm conditions, such as loss of flow or high temperature, to be displayed and recorded.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] PLCs can range from small modular devices with tens of inputs and outputs (I/O) in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs, extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Initially, control was from panels local to the process plant.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] However, this required personnel to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently staffed central control room.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Often, the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were individually transmitted back to the plant in the form of pneumatic or electrical signals.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Effectively, this was the centralisation of all the localised panels, with the advantages of reduced manpower requirements and a consolidated overview of the process.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, so system changes required reconfiguration of signals by re-piping or re-wiring.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] It also required continual operator movement within a large control room in order to monitor the whole process.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] With the coming of electronic processors, high-speed electronic signalling networks and electronic graphic displays, it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] These could be distributed around the plant and would communicate with the graphic displays in the control room.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The concept of *distributed control* was realised.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The introduction of distributed control allowed flexible interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] For large control systems, the general commercial name *distributed control system* (DCS) was coined to refer to proprietary modular systems from many manufacturers that integrated high-speed networking and a full suite of displays and control racks.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] While the DCS was tailored to meet the needs of large continuous industrial processes, in industries where combinatorial and sequential logic was the primary requirement, the PLC evolved out of a need to replace racks of relays and timers used for event-driven control.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The old controls were difficult to reconfigure and debug, and PLC control enabled networking of signals to a central control area with electronic displays.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] PLCs were first developed for the automotive industry on vehicle production lines, where sequential logic was becoming very complex.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] It was soon adopted in a large number of other event-driven applications as varied as printing presses and water treatment plants.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] SCADA's history is rooted in distribution applications, such as power, natural gas, and water pipelines, where there is a need to gather remote data through potentially unreliable or intermittent low-bandwidth and high-latency links.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] SCADA systems use open-loop control with sites that are widely separated geographically.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] A SCADA system uses remote terminal units (RTUs) to send supervisory data back to a control centre.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Most RTU systems always had some capacity to handle local control while the master station is not available.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] However, over the years, RTU systems have grown more and more capable of handling local control.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The boundaries between DCS and SCADA/PLC systems are blurring as time goes on.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The technical limits that drove the designs of these various systems are no longer as much of an issue.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Many PLC platforms can now perform quite well as a small DCS, using remote I/O and are sufficiently reliable that some SCADA systems actually manage closed-loop control over long distances.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] With the increasing speed of today's processors, many DCS products have a full line of PLC-like subsystems that weren't offered when they were initially developed.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] In 1993, with the release of IEC-1131, later to become IEC-61131-3, the industry moved towards increased code standardization with reusable, hardware-independent control software.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] For the first time, object-oriented programming (OOP) became possible within industrial control systems.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] This led to the development of both programmable automation controllers (PAC) and industrial PCs (IPC).
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] These are platforms programmed in the five standardized IEC languages: ladder logic, structured text, function block, instruction list and sequential function chart.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] They can also be programmed in modern high-level languages such as C or C++.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Additionally, they accept models developed in analytical tools such as MATLAB and Simulink.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Unlike traditional PLCs, which use proprietary operating systems, IPCs utilize Windows IoT.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] IPCs have the advantage of powerful multi-core processors with much lower hardware costs than traditional PLCs and fit well into multiple form factors such as DIN rail mount, combined with a touch-screen as a panel PC, or as an embedded PC.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] New hardware platforms and technology have contributed significantly to the evolution of DCS and SCADA systems, further blurring the boundaries and changing definitions.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] SCADA and PLCs are vulnerable to cyber attack.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] Government Joint Capability Technology Demonstration (JCTD) known as MOSAICS (More Situational Awareness for Industrial Control Systems) is the initial demonstration of cybersecurity defensive capability for critical infrastructure control systems.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] MOSAICS addresses the Department of Defense (DOD) operational need for cyber defense capabilities to defend critical infrastructure control systems from cyber attack, such as power, water and wastewater, and safety controls, affect the physical environment.
[src:plc-scada/industrial-control-system] The MOSAICS JCTD prototype will be shared with commercial industry through Industry Days for further research and development, an approach intended to lead to an innovative, game-changing capabilities for cybersecurity for critical infrastructure control systems.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Ladder logic has evolved into a programming language that represents a program by a graphical diagram based on the circuit diagrams of relay logic hardware.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Ladder logic is used to develop software for programmable logic controllers (PLCs) used in industrial control applications.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] The name is based on the observation that programs in this language resemble ladders, with two vertical rails and a series of horizontal rungs between them.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Ladder diagrams were once the only way to record programmable controller programs, but today, other forms are standardized in IEC 61131-3.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] For example, instead of the graphical ladder logic form, there is a language called Structured text, which is similar to C, within the IEC 61131-3 standard.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Ladder logic is widely used to program PLCs, where sequential control of a process or manufacturing operation is required.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Ladder logic is useful for simple but critical control systems or for reworking old hardwired relay circuits.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] As programmable logic controllers became more sophisticated it has also been used in very complex automation systems.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Often the ladder logic program is used in conjunction with a human–machine interface (HMI) program operating on a computer workstation.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] The motivation for representing sequential control logic in a ladder diagram was to allow factory engineers and technicians to develop software without additional training to learn a language such as FORTRAN or other general-purpose computer language.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Development and maintenance were simplified because of the resemblance to familiar relay hardware systems.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Implementations of ladder logic may have characteristics, such as sequential execution and support for control flow features, that make the analogy to hardware somewhat inaccurate.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Ladder logic can be thought of as a rule-based language rather than a procedural language.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] A "rung" in the ladder represents a rule.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] When implemented with relays and other electro-mechanical devices, the various rules execute simultaneously and immediately.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] When implemented in a programmable logic controller, the rules are typically executed sequentially by software in a continuous loop, or "scan".
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] By executing the loop fast enough, typically many times per second, the effect of simultaneous and immediate execution is achieved.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Proper use of programmable controllers requires an understanding of the limitations of the execution order of rungs.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] The language itself can be seen as a set of connections between logical checkers (contacts) and actuators (coils).
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] When a path exists from the left side of the rung to the output through asserted (true or "closed") contacts, the rung is considered true, and the output coil storage bit is set to 1 or (true).
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] If no such path exists, the output is false (0), and the "coil" by analogy to electromechanical relays is considered "de-energized".
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] This analogy between logical propositions and relay contact status was established by Claude Shannon.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Ladder logic has contacts that make or break circuits to control coils.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Each coil or contact corresponds to the status of a single bit in the programmable controller's memory.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Unlike electromechanical relays, a ladder program can refer any number of times to the status of a single bit, equivalent to a relay with an indefinitely large number of contacts.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] So-called "contacts" may refer to physical ("hard") inputs to the programmable controller from physical devices such as pushbuttons and limit switches via an integrated or external input module, or may represent the status of internal storage bits which may be generated elsewhere in the program.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Each rung of ladder language typically has one coil at the far right.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Some manufacturers may allow more than one output coil on a rung.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] The "coil" (output of a rung) may represent a physical output which operates some device connected to the programmable controller, or may represent an internal storage bit for use elsewhere in the program.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] A way to recall these is to imagine the checkers (contacts) as a push button input, and the actuators (coils) as a light bulb output.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] The presence of a slash within the checkers or actuators would indicate the default state of the device at rest.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] This circuit shows two key switches that security guards might use to activate an electric motor on a bank vault door.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] When the normally open contacts of both switches close, electricity is able to flow to the motor which opens the door.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] The above realizes the function: Door motor = Close door AND NOT Obstruction.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] This circuit shows a push button that closes a door and an obstruction detector that senses if something is in the way of the closing door.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] When the normally open push button contact closes and the normally closed (NC) obstruction detector is closed (no obstruction detected), electricity is able to flow to the motor which closes the door.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] This circuit shows the two things that can trigger a car's power door locks.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] The unlock solenoid gets power when either set of contacts is closed.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] In common industrial latching start/stop logic, we have a "Start" button to turn on a motor contactor, and a "Stop" button to turn off the contactor.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] When the "Start" button is pushed the input goes true, via the "Stop" button NC contact.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] When the "Run" input becomes true the seal-in "Run" NO contact in parallel with the "Start" NO contact will close maintaining the input logic true (latched or sealed-in).
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] After the circuit is latched the "Stop" button may be pushed causing its NC contact to open and consequently the input to go false.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] The "Run" NO contact then opens and the circuit logic returns to its inactive state.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] This latch configuration is a common idiom in ladder logic.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] It may also be referred to as *seal-in logic*.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] The key to understanding the latch is in recognizing that the "Start" switch is a momentary switch (once the user releases the button, the switch is open again).
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] As soon as the "Run" solenoid engages, it closes the "Run" NO contact, which latches the solenoid on.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] The "Start" switch opening up then has no effect.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] For safety reasons, an emergency stop ("ES") may be hardwired in series with the "Start" switch, and the relay logic should reflect this.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Note, that when being really safe, the physical contacts for stop and emergency stop are wired such that the PLC is given HIGH (true) inputs, when the buttons are NOT pressed, hence the PLC logic should be reversed for those.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Here is an example of what two rungs in a ladder logic program might look like.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] In real-world applications, there may be hundreds or thousands of rungs.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Typically, complex ladder logic is "read" left to right and top to bottom.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] As each of the lines (or rungs) are evaluated the output coil of a rung may feed into the next stage of the ladder as an input.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Realising the function: Cooling = A/C AND (NOT Heat).
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] This represents a slightly more complex system for rung 2.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] After the first line has been evaluated, the output coil "A/C" is fed into rung 2, which is then evaluated and the output coil "Cooling" could be fed into an output device "Compressor" or into rung 3 on the ladder.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] This system allows very complex logic designs to be broken down and evaluated.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Additional functionality can be added to a ladder logic implementation by the PLC manufacturer as a special block.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] When the special block is powered, it executes code on predetermined arguments.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] These arguments may be displayed within the special block.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] In this example, the system will count the number of times that the interior and remote unlock buttons are pressed.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] This information will be stored in memory locations A and B.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Memory location C will hold the total number of times that the door has been unlocked electronically.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] They include timers, arithmetic operators and comparisons, table lookups, text processing, PID control, and filtering functions.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] More powerful PLCs can operate on a group of internal memory locations and execute an operation on a range of addresses, for example, to simulate a physical sequential drum controller or a finite-state machine.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] In some cases, users can define their own special blocks, which effectively are subroutines or macros.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] The large library of special blocks along with high-speed execution has allowed use of PLCs to implement very complex automation systems.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Ladder notation is best suited to control problems where only binary variables are required and where interlocking and sequencing of binary is the primary control problem.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Like all parallel programming languages, the sequential order of operations may be undefined or obscure; logic race conditions are possible which may produce unexpected results.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Complex rungs are best broken into several simpler steps to avoid this problem.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Some manufacturers avoid this problem by explicitly and completely defining the execution order of a rung, however, programmers may still have problems fully grasping the resulting complex semantics.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Analog quantities and arithmetical operations are clumsy to express in ladder logic and each manufacturer has different ways of extending the notation for these problems.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] There is usually limited support for arrays and loops, often resulting in duplication of code to express cases that in other languages would call for use of indexed variables.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] As microprocessors have become more powerful, notations such as sequential function charts and function block diagrams can replace ladder logic for some limited applications.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] Some newer PLCs may have all or part of the programming carried out in a dialect that resembles BASIC, C, or other programming language with bindings appropriate for a real-time application environment.
[src:plc-scada/ladder-logic] In 2019, *IEEE Spectrum* ranked ladder logic as number 50 out of 52 in a list of popular programming languages.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Although developed by the same organization, OPC UA differs significantly from its predecessor, Open Platform Communications (OPC).
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The Foundation's goal for OPC UA was to provide a path forward from the original OPC communications model (namely the Microsoft Windows-only process exchange COM/DCOM) that would better meet the emerging needs of industrial automation.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] After more than three years of specification work and another year for a prototype implementation, the first version of the Unified Architecture was released in 2006.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The current version of the specification is on 1.04 (22 November 2017).
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The new version of OPC UA now has added publish/subscribe in addition to the client/server communications infrastructure.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] These drawbacks along with a number of other considerations pushed the decision to develop a new and independent stack for OPC UA, which replaces COM/DCOM.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] This communication stack reflects the beginning of various innovations.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The OPC UA architecture is a service-oriented architecture (SOA) and is based on different logical levels.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] OPC Base Services are abstract method descriptions, which are protocol independent and provide the basis for OPC UA functionality.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The transport layer puts these methods into a protocol, which means it serializes/deserializes the data and transmits it over the network.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Two protocols are specified for this purpose.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] One is a binary TCP protocol, optimized for high performance and the second is Web service-oriented.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The OPC information model is a Mesh Network based on nodes.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] These nodes can include any kind of meta information, and are similar to the objects of object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] A node can have attributes for read access such as DataAccess (DA), HistoricDataAccess (HDA), methods that can be called (Commands), and triggered events that can be transmitted (such as AlarmEvent (AE), DataAccess, and DataChange).
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Nodes hold process data as well as other types of metadata.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The OPC namespace contains the type-model.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The namespace is a URI that identifies the naming authority responsible for assigning the identifier element of the NodeId.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Naming authorities include the local Server, the underlying system, standards bodies and consortia.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] It is expected that most Nodes will use the URI of the Server or of the underlying system.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Client software can verify what profiles a server supports.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] This is necessary to obtain information, if a server only supports DA functionality or additionally AE, HDA, etc.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Additionally, information can be obtained about whether a server supports a given profile.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] At the OPC UA DevCon in October 2006, in Munich the first prototypes were presented live.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Various UA Servers have been shown on a Beckhoff programmable logic controller and an embedded test board from Euros.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The Beckhoff PLC is based on Windows XP Embedded and the embedded controller is based on the real-time operating system Euros.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The company Embedded Labs Ltd demonstrated an OPC UA Server based on their own C++ UA Stack executing on a single chip ARM microcontroller with 64kB RAM.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] In October 2012 the German Fraunhofer-Application Center IOSB-INA and the Institute for industrial Information Technologies (inIT) showed that an OPC UA server is scalable down to 15 kB RAM and 10 kB ROM and therefore usable at chip level.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The current version of the specification is 1.05.06, and was released on 22 October, 2025.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Additionally, part 100 Devices, and part 200 Industrial Automation are also available.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] These build on the core set of specifications, and adds new common definitions that then are used in different companion specifications.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] E.g. both *OPC UA for Analyser Devices* and *OPC UA for Machinery* builds directly on part 100.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] In contrast to the COM-based specifications, the UA specifications are not pure application specifications.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] They describe typical UA internal mechanisms, which get handled through the communication stack and are normally only of interest for those that port a stack to a specific target or those that want to implement their own UA stack.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The OPC UA application developers code against the OPC UA API and therefore mainly use API documentation.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Nevertheless, part 3, 4, and 5 may be of interest for application developers.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] OPC UA is a versatile industrial communication protocol that is designed to be transport-agnostic, and operate over several transport mechanisms, each corresponding to different layers of the OSI model.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] It can use, TCP, UDP or Ethernet directly, or it can also be encapsulated within higher-level application protocols such as HTTPS, WebSockets, AMQP, and MQTT.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The architecture of a UA application, independent of whether it is the server or client part, is structured into levels.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Some parts equalize to the former COM Proxy/Stubs and get provided by the OPC Foundation.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The portability level is new; it simplifies porting the UA ANSI C stack to other target platforms.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] A port layer for Windows and Linux is also provided by the OPC Foundation.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] UA Security consists of authentication and authorization, encryption and data integrity via signatures.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] For Web Services the WS-SecureConversation gets used and is therefore compatible with .NET and other SO–AP implementations.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] For the binary variant, the algorithms of WS-SecureConversation have been followed and also converted to a binary equivalent.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] This is named as UA Secure Conversation.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] There is also a mixed version where the code is binary, but the transport layer is SOAP.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] This is a compromise between efficient binary coding and firewall-friendly transmission.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Binary coding always requires UA Secure Conversation.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The authentication uses X.509 certificates exclusively.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] It relies on the application developer to choose which certificate store the UA application gets bound to.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] For instance, it is possible to use the public key infrastructure (PKI) of an Active Directory.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] UA APIs are available in several programming languages.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Commercial SDKs are available for C, C++, Java, and .NET.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Open-source stacks are available at least for C, C++, Java, JavaScript(node), Tcl and Python.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The .NET implementation uses ANSI C for the lower levels and implements the rest natively in .NET.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] That means only the handling of the socket and the Message-Chunking gets integrated from the ANSI C stack.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] De-serialization takes place directly in .NET and therefore gets converted directly into .NET structures and objects.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] This provides better performance than de-serializing into a C structure first and then copying the data to a .NET structure afterwards.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Various stacks for Java were being developed.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Code directly on the network layer (similar to the current .Net implementation) and de-serialize in Java.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] This saves one data copy execution, but still depends on the C stack.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] This was observed to be the most portable, but estimated to take the most engineering effort to implement.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] The Eclipse Milo project provides a pure-Java, open-source, implementation of the UA 1.05 client and server specification.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Apache PLC4X project provides pure-Java, open-source implementation of UA client as well as network level frame descriptions which can be used for cross-language implementations.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] Alternatively, there is the simple variant to only support the WebService protocol.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] For that, a SOAP Toolkit that supports WS-Security is needed.
[src:plc-scada/opc-unified-architecture] IEC 62541 is a standard for OPC Unified Architecture.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs can range from small modular devices with tens of inputs and outputs (I/O), in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] They can be designed for many arrangements of digital and analog I/O, extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs were first developed in the automobile manufacturing industry to provide flexible, rugged and easily programmable controllers to replace hard-wired relay logic systems.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Dick Morley, who invented the first PLC, the Modicon 084, for General Motors in 1968, is considered the father of PLC.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC is an example of a hard real-time system since output results must be produced in response to input conditions within a limited time, otherwise unintended operation may result.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC originated in the late 1960s in the automotive industry in the US and was designed to replace relay logic systems.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Before, control logic for manufacturing was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The hard-wired nature of these components made it difficult for design engineers to alter the automation process.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Changes would require rewiring and careful updating of the documentation.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] When general-purpose computers became available, they were soon applied to control logic in industrial processes.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These early computers were unreliable and required specialist programmers and strict control of working conditions, such as temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC provided several advantages over earlier automation systems.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It was designed to tolerate the industrial environment better than systems intended for office use, and was more reliable, compact, and required less maintenance than relay systems.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It was easily expandable with additional I/O modules.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] While relay systems required tedious and sometimes complicated hardware changes in case of reconfiguration, a PLC can be reconfigured by loading new or modified code.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] This allowed for easier iteration over manufacturing process design.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] With a simple programming language focused on logic and switching operations, it was more user-friendly than computers using general-purpose programming languages.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Early PLCs were programmed in ladder logic, which strongly resembled a schematic diagram of relay logic.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It also permitted its operation to be monitored.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In recent years, the introduction of virtual PLCs has expanded the scope of programmable logic controllers.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Virtual PLCs are software-based controllers that simulate the functions of traditional PLCs but are executed on general-purpose hardware, offering a more cost-effective and flexible alternative.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These controllers enable automation systems to be managed without the need for dedicated hardware, making them ideal for applications requiring simulation, remote control, or cloud-based systems.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In 1968, GM Hydramatic, the automatic transmission division of General Motors, issued a request for proposals for an electronic replacement for hard-wired relay systems based on a white paper written by engineer Edward R.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The winning proposal came from Bedford Associates from Bedford, Massachusetts.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The result, built in 1969, was the first PLC and designated the *084*, because it was Bedford Associates' eighty-fourth project.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Bedford Associates started a company, **Modicon, Inc.**, dedicated to developing, manufacturing, selling, and servicing this new product, which they named **Modicon** (standing for "modular digital controller").
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] One of the people who worked on that project was Dick Morley, who is considered to be the father of the PLC.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The Modicon brand was sold in 1977 to Gould Electronics and later to Schneider Electric, its current owner.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] About this same time, Modicon created Modbus, a data communications protocol to be used with its PLCs.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Modbus has since become a standard open protocol commonly used to connect many industrial electrical devices.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] One of the first Modicon 084 models built is now on display at Schneider Electric's facility in North Andover, Massachusetts.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It was presented to Modicon by GM, when the unit was retired after nearly twenty years of uninterrupted service.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Modicon used the 84 moniker at the end of its product range like Modicon Micro 84 and Modicon TSX CSY 84 until after the 984 made its appearance.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In a parallel development, Odo Josef Struger is sometimes known as the "father of the programmable logic controller" as well.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] He was involved in the invention of the Allen-Bradley programmable logic controller.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Prior to the release of the IBM "Personal Computer" in 1981, these devices were commonly known simply as "Programmable Controllers", or "PC's.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] But rapid expansion of the personal computer industry in the early 1980's, the abbreviation "PC" was rapidly and universally accepted as a reference to "Personal Computers".
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Odo was later credited with coining the "PLC" acronym to distinguish these two technologies, And the inclusion of the word "Logic" was an easy choice as "Ladder Logic" had already been accepted as the name of the programming language.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Allen-Bradley (now a brand owned by Rockwell Automation) went on to become the dominant PLC manufacturer in the United States during his tenure.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Struger played a leadership role in developing IEC 61131-3 PLC programming language standards.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Allen-Bradley's PLC-5 family, preceded by the 1774-PLC (released in the 1980's, was the first modular design found in modern-day systems.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] While Modicon was the most popular of the first full featured PLC's through the early 1980's, Allen Bradley overtook them in the mid-1980's and grew to own the largest market share of PLC hardware and software in North America.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Many early PLC programming applications were not capable of graphical representation of the logic, and so it was instead represented as a series of logic expressions in some kind of Boolean format, similar to Boolean algebra.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] As programming terminals evolved, because ladder logic was a familiar format used for electro-mechanical control panels, it became more commonly used.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Newer formats, such as state logic, function block diagrams, and structured text exist.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Ladder logic remains popular because PLCs solve the logic in a predictable and repeating sequence, and ladder logic allows the person writing the logic to see any issues with the timing of the logic sequence more easily than would be possible in other formats.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Up to the mid-1990s, PLCs were programmed using proprietary programming panels or special-purpose programming terminals, which often had dedicated function keys representing the various logical elements of PLC programs.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Some proprietary programming terminals displayed the elements of PLC programs as graphic symbols, but plain ASCII character representations of contacts, coils, and wires were common.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Programs were stored on cassette tape cartridges.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Facilities for printing and documentation were minimal due to a lack of memory capacity.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The oldest PLCs used magnetic-core memory.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC is an industrial microprocessor-based controller with programmable memory used to store program instructions and various functions.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs require a programming device that is used to develop and later download the created program into the memory of the controller.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Modern PLCs generally contain a real-time operating system, such as OS-9 or VxWorks.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] There are two types of mechanical design for PLC systems.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A *single box* (also called a *brick*) is a small programmable controller that fits all units and interfaces into one compact casing, although, typically, additional expansion modules for inputs and outputs are available.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The second design type – a *modular* PLC – has a chassis (also called a *rack*) that provides space for modules with different functions, such as power supply, processor, selection of I/O modules and communication interfaces – which all can be customized for the particular application.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Several racks can be administered by a single processor and may have thousands of inputs and outputs.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Either a special high-speed serial I/O link or comparable communication method is used so that racks can be distributed away from the processor, reducing the wiring costs for large plants.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Discrete (digital) signals can only take *on* or *off* value (1 or 0, *true* or *false*).
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Examples of devices providing a discrete signal include limit switches and photoelectric sensors.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Analog signals can use voltage or current that is analogous to the monitored variable and can take any value within their scale.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Pressure, temperature, flow, and weight are often represented by analog signals.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These are typically interpreted as integer values with various ranges of accuracy depending on the device and the number of bits available to store the data.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] For example, an analog 0 to 10 V or 4-20 mA current loop input would be converted into an integer value of 0 to 32,767.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC will take this value and translate it into the desired units of the process so the operator or program can read it.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Some special processes need to work permanently with minimum unwanted downtime.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Therefore, it is necessary to design a system that is fault tolerant.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In such cases, to increase the system availability in the event of hardware component failure, redundant CPU or I/O modules with the same functionality can be added to a hardware configuration to prevent a total or partial process shutdown due to hardware failure.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Other redundancy scenarios could be related to safety-critical processes, for example, large hydraulic presses could require that two PLCs turn on an output before the press can come down in case one PLC does not behave properly.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Programmable logic controllers are intended to be used by engineers without a programming background.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] For this reason, a graphical programming language called ladder logic was first developed.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It resembles the schematic diagram of a system built with electromechanical relays and was adopted by many manufacturers and later standardized in the IEC 61131-3 control systems programming standard.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] As of 2015, it is still widely used, thanks to its simplicity.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] As of 2015, the majority of PLC systems adhere to the IEC 61131-3 standard that defines two textual programming languages: Structured Text (similar to Pascal) and Instruction List; as well as three graphical languages: ladder logic, function block diagram and sequential function chart.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Instruction List was deprecated in the third edition of the standard.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Modern PLCs can be programmed in a variety of ways, from the relay-derived ladder logic to programming languages such as specially adapted dialects of BASIC and C.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] While the fundamental concepts of PLC programming are common to all manufacturers, differences in I/O addressing, memory organization, and instruction sets mean that PLC programs are never perfectly interchangeable between different makers.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Even within the same product line of a single manufacturer, different models may not be directly compatible.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Manufacturers develop programming software for their PLCs.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In addition to being able to program PLCs in multiple languages, they provide common features like hardware diagnostics and maintenance, software debugging, and offline simulation.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLC programs are typically written in a programming device, which can take the form of a desktop console, special software on a personal computer, or a handheld device.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The program is then downloaded to the PLC through a cable connection or over a network.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It is stored either in non-volatile flash memory or battery-backed-up RAM on the PLC.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In some PLCs, the program is transferred from the programming device using a programming board that writes the program into a removable chip, such as EPROM, that is then inserted into the PLC.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] An incorrectly programmed PLC can result in lost productivity and dangerous conditions for programmed equipment.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLC simulation is a feature often found in PLC programming software.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It allows for testing and debugging early in a project's development.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Testing the project in simulation improves its quality, increases the level of safety associated with equipment and can save time during the installation and commissioning of automated control applications since many scenarios can be tried and tested before the system is activated.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The main difference compared to most other computing devices is that PLCs are intended for and therefore tolerant of more severe environmental conditions (such as dust, moisture, heat, cold), while offering extensive input/output (I/O) to connect the PLC to sensors and actuators.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLC input can include simple digital elements such as limit switches, analog variables from process sensors (such as temperature and pressure), and more complex data such as that from positioning or machine vision systems.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLC output can include elements such as indicator lamps, sirens, electric motors, pneumatic or hydraulic cylinders, magnetic relays, solenoids, or analog outputs.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The input/output arrangements may be built into a simple PLC, or the PLC may have external I/O modules attached to a fieldbus or computer network that plugs into the PLC.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The functionality of the PLC has evolved over the years to include sequential relay control, motion control, process control, distributed control systems, and networking.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The data handling, storage, processing power, and communication capabilities of some modern PLCs are approximately equivalent to desktop computers.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLC-like programming combined with remote I/O hardware allows a general-purpose desktop computer to serve as a PLC in certain applications.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The most basic function of a programmable logic controller is to emulate the functions of electromechanical relays.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Within the PLC programming environment, discrete inputs are given a unique address, and a PLC instruction can test if the input state is on or off.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Just as a series of relay contacts performs a logical AND function, not allowing current to pass unless all the contacts are closed, so a series of *examine if on* instructions will energize its output storage bit if all the input bits are on.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Similarly, a parallel set of instructions will perform a logical OR.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In an electromechanical relay wiring diagram, a group of contacts controlling one coil is called a *rung* of a *ladder diagram*, and this concept is also used to describe PLC logic.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The output of each rung sets or clears a storage bit, which may be associated with a discrete output or which may be an *internal coil* with no physical connection.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Such internal coils can be used, for example, as a common element in multiple separate rungs.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] More advanced instructions of the PLC may be implemented as functional blocks, which carry out some operation, such as manipulating an internal variable, when enabled by a logical input and which produce outputs to signal, for example, completion or errors.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs use built-in ports, such as USB, Ethernet, RS-232, RS-485, or RS-422 to communicate with external devices (sensors, actuators) and systems (programming tools, SCADA and other user interfaces).
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Communication is carried over various industrial network protocols, like Modbus, or EtherNet/IP.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Many of these protocols are vendor specific.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Formerly, some manufacturers offered dedicated communication modules as an add-on function where the processor had no network connection built in.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs used in larger I/O systems may have peer-to-peer (P2P) communication between processors.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] This allows separate parts of a complex process to have individual control while allowing the subsystems to coordinate over the communication link.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs may need to interact with people for the purpose of configuration, alarm reporting, or everyday control.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A human-machine interface (HMI) is employed for this purpose.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] HMIs are also referred to as man-machine interfaces (MMIs) and graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A simple system may use buttons and lights to interact with the user.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Text displays are available as well as graphical touch screens.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] More complex systems use programming and monitoring software installed on a computer, with the PLC connected via a communication interface.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC works in a program scan cycle, where it executes its program repeatedly.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The program follows the sequence of instructions.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It typically takes a time span of tens of milliseconds for the processor to evaluate all the instructions and update the status of all outputs.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] If the system contains remote I/O—for example, an external rack with I/O modules—then that introduces additional uncertainty in the response time of the PLC system.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Special-purpose I/O modules may be used where the scan time of the PLC is too long to allow predictable performance.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Precision timing modules, or counter modules for use with shaft encoders, are used where the scan time would be too long to reliably count pulses or detect the sense of rotation of an encoder.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] This allows even a relatively slow PLC to still interpret the counted values to control a machine, as the accumulation of pulses is done by a dedicated module that is unaffected by the speed of program execution.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] As PLCs became more advanced, methods were developed to change the sequence of ladder execution, and subroutines were implemented.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Prior to the discovery of the Stuxnet computer worm in June 2010, the security of PLCs received little attention.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Modern programmable controllers generally contain real-time operating systems, which can be vulnerable to exploits in a similar way as desktop operating systems.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs can also be attacked by gaining control of a computer they communicate with.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Since 2011, these concerns have grown as networking is becoming more commonplace in the PLC environment, connecting the previously separated plant floor networks and office networks.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In February 2021, Rockwell Automation publicly disclosed a critical vulnerability affecting its Logix controller family.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The secret cryptographic key used to verify communication between the PLC and workstation could be extracted from the programming software (Studio 5000 Logix Designer) and used to remotely change program code and configuration of a connected controller.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The vulnerability was given a severity score of 10 out of 10 on the Common Vulnerability Scoring System.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Safety PLCs can be either a standalone device or safety-rated hardware and functionality added to existing controller architectures (Allen-Bradley GuardLogix, Siemens F-series, etc.).
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These differ from conventional PLC types by being suitable for safety-critical applications for which PLCs have traditionally been supplemented with hard-wired safety relays and areas of the memory dedicated to the safety instructions.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The standard of safety level is the safety integrity level (SIL).
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A safety PLC might be used to control access to a robot cell with trapped-key access, or to manage the shutdown response to an emergency stop button on a conveyor production line.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Such PLCs typically have a restricted regular instruction set augmented with safety-specific instructions designed to interface with emergency stop buttons, light screens, and other safety-related devices.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs are well adapted to a range of automation tasks.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These are typically industrial processes in manufacturing where the cost of developing and maintaining the automation system is high relative to the total cost of the automation system, and where changes to the system would be expected during its operational life.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs contain input and output devices compatible with industrial devices and controls; little electrical design is required, and the design problem centers on expressing the desired sequence of operations.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLC applications are typically highly customized systems, so the cost of a packaged PLC is low compared to the cost of a specific custom-built controller design.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] On the other hand, in the case of mass-produced goods, customized control systems are economical.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] This is due to the lower cost of the components, which can be optimally chosen instead of a *generic* solution, and where the non-recurring engineering charges are spread over thousands or millions of units.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These are for small machines and systems with low or medium volume.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] They can execute PLC languages such as ladder logic, function block diagram and sequential function chart.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] They are similar to traditional PLCs, but their small size allows developers to design them into custom printed circuit boards like a microcontroller, without computer programming knowledge, but with a language that is easy to use, modify and maintain.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Architecturally, they sit between the classic PLC or micro-PLC and microcontrollers.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Automotive applications are an example; millions of units are built each year, and very few end-users alter the programming of these controllers.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] However, some specialty vehicles, such as transit buses, economically use PLCs instead of custom-designed controllers, because the volumes are low and the development cost would be uneconomical.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Very complex process control, such as that used in the chemical industry, may require algorithms and performance beyond the capability of even high-performance PLCs.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Very high-speed or precision controls may also require customized solutions; for example, aircraft flight controls.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Single-board computers using semi-customized or fully proprietary hardware may be chosen for very demanding control applications where the high development and maintenance cost can be supported.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] **Soft PLCs** running on desktop-type computers can interface with industrial I/O hardware while executing programs within a version of commercial operating systems adapted for process control needs.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The rising popularity of single-board computers has also had an influence on the development of PLCs.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Traditional PLCs are generally closed platforms, but some newer PLCs (e.g., groov EPIC from Opto 22, ctrlX from Bosch Rexroth, PFC200 from Wago, PLCnext from Phoenix Contact, and Revolution Pi from Kunbus) provide the features of traditional PLCs on an open platform.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In more recent years, small products called programmable logic relays (PLRs) or smart relays have become more common and accepted.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These are similar to PLCs and are used in light industries where only a few points of I/O are needed, and low cost is desired.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These small devices are typically made in a common physical size and shape by several manufacturers and branded by the makers of larger PLCs to fill their low-end product range.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Most of these have 8 to 12 discrete inputs, 4 to 8 discrete outputs, and up to 2 analog inputs.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Most have an RS-232 or RS-485 port for connecting to a PC so that programmers can use user-friendly software for programming instead of the small LCD and push-button set for this purpose.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Unlike regular PLCs that are usually modular and greatly expandable, the PLRs are usually not modular or expandable, but their cost can be significantly lower than that a PLC, and they still offer robust design and deterministic execution of the logic.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A variant of PLCs, used in remote locations, is the remote terminal unit or RTU.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] An RTU is typically a low power, ruggedized PLC whose key function is to manage the communications links between the site and the central control system (typically SCADA) or in some modern systems, "The Cloud".
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Unlike factory automation using wired communication protocols such as Ethernet, communications links to remote sites are often radio-based and are less reliable.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] To account for the reduced reliability, RTU will buffer messages or switch to alternate communications paths.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] When buffering messages, the RTU will timestamp each message so that a full history of site events can be reconstructed.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] RTUs, being PLCs, have a wide range of I/O and are fully programmable, typically with languages from the IEC 61131-3 standard that is common to many PLCs, RTUs and DCSs.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In remote locations, it is common to use an RTU as a gateway for a PLC, where the PLC is performing all site control and the RTU is managing communications, time-stamping events and monitoring ancillary equipment.
[src:plc-scada/programmable-logic-controller] On sites with only a handful of I/O, the RTU may also be the site PLC and will perform both communications and control functions.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA computer system.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The subordinated operations, e.g. the real-time control logic or controller calculations, are performed by networked modules connected to the field sensors and actuators.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The SCADA concept was developed to be a universal means of remote-access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers and allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:plc-scada/scada] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become similar to DCSs in function, while using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:plc-scada/scada] They can control large-scale processes spanning multiple sites, and work over large distances.
[src:plc-scada/scada] It is one of the most commonly used types of industrial control systems.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The key attribute of a SCADA system is its ability to perform a supervisory operation over a variety of other proprietary devices.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Level 1 contains the programmable logic controllers (PLCs) or remote terminal units (RTUs).
[src:plc-scada/scada] Level 2 contains the SCADA to readings and equipment status reports that are communicated to level 2 SCADA as required.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Data is then compiled and formatted in such a way that a control room operator using the human-machine interface (HMI) can make supervisory decisions to adjust or override normal RTU (PLC) controls.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Data may also be fed to a historian, often built on a commodity database management system, to allow trending and other analytical auditing.
[src:plc-scada/scada] SCADA systems typically use a *tag database*, which contains data elements called *tags* or *points*, which relate to specific instrumentation or actuators within the process system.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Data is accumulated against these unique process control equipment tag references.
[src:plc-scada/scada] This is the core of the SCADA system, gathering data on the process and sending control commands to the field connected devices.
[src:plc-scada/scada] It refers to the computer and software responsible for communicating with the field connection controllers, which are RTUs and PLCs, and includes the HMI software running on operator workstations.
[src:plc-scada/scada] In smaller SCADA systems, the supervisory computer may be composed of a single PC, in which case the HMI is a part of this computer.
[src:plc-scada/scada] In larger SCADA systems, the master station may include several HMIs hosted on client computers, multiple servers for data acquisition, distributed software applications, and disaster recovery sites.
[src:plc-scada/scada] formation providing continuous control and monitoring in the event of a server malfunction or breakdown.
[src:plc-scada/scada] connect to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory computer system.
[src:plc-scada/scada] system, using radio, GSM or satellite for communications, and being ruggedised to survive from -20C to +70C or even -40C to +85C without external heating or cooling equipment.
[src:plc-scada/scada] PLCs are connected to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory system.
[src:plc-scada/scada] In factory automation, PLCs typically have a high speed connection to the SCADA system.
[src:plc-scada/scada] In remote applications, such as a large water treatment plant, PLCs may connect directly to SCADA over a wireless link, or more commonly, utilise an RTU for the communications management.
[src:plc-scada/scada] For economical reasons, PLCs are often used for remote sites where there is a large I/O count, rather than utilising an RTU alone.
[src:plc-scada/scada] This connects the supervisory computer system to the RTUs and PLCs, and may use industry standard or manufacturer proprietary protocols.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Both RTUs and PLCs operate autonomously on the near-real time control of the process, using the last command given from the supervisory system.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Failure of the communications network does not necessarily stop the plant process controls, and on resumption of communications, the operator can continue with monitoring and control.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Some critical systems will have dual redundant data highways, often cabled via diverse routes.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The HMI is the operator window of the supervisory system.
[src:plc-scada/scada] It presents plant information to the operating personnel graphically in the form of mimic diagrams, which are a schematic representation of the plant being controlled, and alarm and event logging pages.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The HMI is linked to the SCADA supervisory computer to provide live data to drive the mimic diagrams, alarm displays and trending graphs.
[src:plc-scada/scada] In many installations the HMI is the graphical user interface for the operator, collects all data from external devices, creates reports, performs alarming, sends notifications, etc.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Mimic diagrams consist of line graphics and schematic symbols to represent process elements, or may consist of digital photographs of the process equipment overlain with animated symbols.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Supervisory operation of the plant is by means of the HMI, with operators issuing commands using mouse pointers, keyboards and touch screens.
[src:plc-scada/scada] For example, a symbol of a pump can show the operator that the pump is running, and a flow meter symbol can show how much fluid it is pumping through the pipe.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The operator can switch the pump off from the mimic by a mouse click or screen touch.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The HMI will show the flow rate of the fluid in the pipe decrease in real time.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The HMI package for a SCADA system typically includes a drawing program that the operators or system maintenance personnel use to change the way these points are represented in the interface.
[src:plc-scada/scada] These representations can be as simple as an on-screen traffic light, which represents the state of an actual traffic light in the field, or as complex as a multi-projector display representing the position of all of the elevators in a skyscraper or all of the trains on a railway.
[src:plc-scada/scada] is a software service within the HMI which accumulates time-stamped data, events, and alarms in a database which can be queried or used to populate graphic trends in the HMI.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The historian is a client that requests data from a data acquisition server.
[src:plc-scada/scada] An important part of most SCADA implementations is alarm handling.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The system monitors whether certain alarm conditions are satisfied, to determine when an alarm event has occurred.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Once an alarm event has been detected, one or more actions are taken (such as the activation of one or more alarm indicators, and perhaps the generation of email or text messages so that management or remote SCADA operators are informed).
[src:plc-scada/scada] In many cases, a SCADA operator may have to acknowledge the alarm event; this may deactivate some alarm indicators, whereas other indicators remain active until the alarm conditions are cleared.
[src:plc-scada/scada] "Smart" RTUs, or standard PLCs, are capable of autonomously executing simple logic processes without involving the supervisory computer.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Unlike a procedural language like C or FORTRAN, IEC 61131-3 has minimal training requirements by virtue of resembling historic physical control arrays.
[src:plc-scada/scada] This allows SCADA system engineers to perform both the design and implementation of a program to be executed on an RTU or PLC.
[src:plc-scada/scada] A programmable automation controller (PAC) is a compact controller that combines the features and capabilities of a PC-based control system with that of a typical PLC.
[src:plc-scada/scada] PACs are deployed in SCADA systems to provide RTU and PLC functions.
[src:plc-scada/scada] In many electrical substation SCADA applications, "distributed RTUs" use information processors or station computers to communicate with digital protective relays, PACs, and other devices for I/O, and communicate with the SCADA master in lieu of a traditional RTU.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Since about 1998, virtually all major PLC manufacturers have offered integrated HMI/SCADA systems, many of them using open and non-proprietary communications protocols.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The Remote Terminal Unit (RTU) connects to physical equipment.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Typically, an RTU converts the electrical signals from the equipment to digital values.
[src:plc-scada/scada] By converting and sending these electrical signals out to equipment the RTU can control equipment.
[src:plc-scada/scada] SCADA systems have traditionally used combinations of radio and direct wired connections, although SONET/SDH is also frequently used for large systems such as railways and power stations.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The remote management or monitoring function of a SCADA system is often referred to as telemetry.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Some users want SCADA data to travel over their pre-established corporate networks or to share the network with other applications.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The legacy of the early low-bandwidth protocols remains, though.
[src:plc-scada/scada] SCADA protocols are designed to be very compact.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Many are designed to send information only when the master station polls the RTU.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Typical legacy SCADA protocols include Modbus RTU, RP-570, Profibus and Conitel.
[src:plc-scada/scada] These communication protocols, with the exception of Modbus (Modbus has been made open by Schneider Electric), are all SCADA-vendor specific but are widely adopted and used.
[src:plc-scada/scada] These communication protocols are standardized and recognized by all major SCADA vendors.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Many of these protocols now contain extensions to operate over TCP/IP.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Although the use of conventional networking specifications, such as TCP/IP, blurs the line between traditional and industrial networking, they each fulfill fundamentally differing requirements.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Network simulation can be used in conjunction with SCADA simulators to perform various 'what-if' analyses.
[src:plc-scada/scada] With increasing security demands (such as North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) and critical infrastructure protection (CIP) in the US), there is increasing use of satellite-based communication.
[src:plc-scada/scada] This has the key advantages that the infrastructure can be self-contained (not using circuits from the public telephone system), can have built-in encryption, and can be engineered to the availability and reliability required by the SCADA system operator.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Earlier experiences using consumer-grade VSAT were poor.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Modern carrier-class systems provide the quality of service required for SCADA.
[src:plc-scada/scada] RTUs and other automatic controller devices were developed before the advent of industry wide standards for interoperability.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The result is that developers and their management created a multitude of control protocols.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Among the larger vendors, there was also the incentive to create their own protocol to "lock in" their customer base.
[src:plc-scada/scada] A list of automation protocols is compiled here.
[src:plc-scada/scada] An example of efforts by vendor groups to standardize automation protocols is the OPC-UA (formerly "OLE for process control" now Open Platform Communications Unified Architecture).
[src:plc-scada/scada] Early SCADA system computing was done by large minicomputers.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Common network services did not exist at the time SCADA was developed.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Thus SCADA systems were independent systems with no connectivity to other systems.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The communication protocols used were strictly proprietary at that time.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The first-generation SCADA system redundancy was achieved using a back-up mainframe system connected to all the remote terminal unit sites and was used in the event of failure of the primary mainframe system.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Some first generation SCADA systems were developed as "turn key" operations that ran on minicomputers such as the PDP-11 series.
[src:plc-scada/scada] SCADA information and command processing were distributed across multiple stations which were connected through a LAN.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Information was shared in near real time.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Each station was responsible for a particular task, which reduced the cost as compared to first generation SCADA.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The network protocols used were still not standardized.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Since these protocols were proprietary, very few people beyond the developers knew enough to determine how secure a SCADA installation was.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Security of the SCADA installation was usually overlooked.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Similar to a distributed architecture, any complex SCADA can be reduced to the simplest components and connected through communication protocols.
[src:plc-scada/scada] In the case of a networked design, the system may be spread across more than one LAN network called a process control network (PCN) and separated geographically.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Several distributed architecture SCADAs running in parallel, with a single supervisor and historian, could be considered a network architecture.
[src:plc-scada/scada] This allows for a more cost-effective solution in very large scale systems.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The growth of the internet has led SCADA systems to implement web technologies allowing users to view data, exchange information and control processes from anywhere in the world through standard web protocols such as HTTPS and WebSocket for live updates.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The early 2000s saw the proliferation of Web SCADA systems.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Web SCADA systems use web browsers such as Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox as the graphical user interface (GUI) for the operators HMI.
[src:plc-scada/scada] This simplifies the client side installation and enables users to access the system from various platforms with web browsers such as servers, personal computers, laptops, tablets and mobile phones.
[src:plc-scada/scada] SCADA systems that tie together decentralized facilities such as power, oil, gas pipelines, water distribution and wastewater collection systems were designed to be open, robust, and easily operated and repaired, but not necessarily secure.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The move from proprietary technologies to more standardized and open solutions together with the increased number of connections between SCADA systems, office networks and the Internet has made them more vulnerable to types of network attacks that are relatively common in computer security.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Security researcher Jerry Brown submitted a similar advisory regarding a buffer overflow vulnerability in a Wonderware InBatchClient ActiveX control.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Both vendors made updates available prior to public vulnerability release.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Mitigation recommendations were standard patching practices and requiring VPN access for secure connectivity.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Consequently, the security of some SCADA-based systems has come into question as they are seen as potentially vulnerable to cyber attacks.
[src:plc-scada/scada] SCADA systems are used to control and monitor physical processes, examples of which are transmission of electricity, transportation of gas and oil in pipelines, water distribution, traffic lights, and other systems used as the basis of modern society.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The security of these SCADA systems is important because compromise or destruction of these systems would impact multiple areas of society far removed from the original compromise.
[src:plc-scada/scada] For example, a blackout caused by a compromised electrical SCADA system would cause financial losses to all the customers that received electricity from that source.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Legacy SCADA deployments can remain difficult to secure because control equipment is often geographically distributed, long-lived, and costly to replace or patch.
[src:plc-scada/scada] There are many threat vectors to a modern SCADA system.
[src:plc-scada/scada] One is the threat of unauthorized access to the control software, whether it is human access or changes induced intentionally or accidentally by virus infections and other software threats residing on the control host machine.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Another is the threat of packet access to the network segments hosting SCADA devices.
[src:plc-scada/scada] In many cases, the control protocol lacks any form of cryptographic security, allowing an attacker to control a SCADA device by sending commands over a network.
[src:plc-scada/scada] In many cases SCADA users have assumed that having a VPN offered sufficient protection, unaware that security can be trivially bypassed with physical access to SCADA-related network jacks and switches.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Industrial control vendors suggest approaching SCADA security like Information Security with a defense in depth strategy that leverages common IT practices.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Apart from that, research has shown that the architecture of SCADA systems has several other vulnerabilities, including direct tampering with RTUs, communication links from RTUs to the control center, and IT software and databases in the control center.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The RTUs could, for instance, be targets of deception attacks injecting false data or denial-of-service attacks.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The reliable function of SCADA systems in our modern infrastructure may be crucial to public health and safety.
[src:plc-scada/scada] As such, attacks on these systems may directly or indirectly threaten public health and safety.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Such an attack has already occurred, carried out on Maroochy Shire Council's sewage control system in Queensland, Australia.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Shortly after a contractor installed a SCADA system in January 2000, system components began to function erratically.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Pumps did not run when needed and alarms were not reported.
[src:plc-scada/scada] More critically, sewage flooded a nearby park and contaminated an open surface-water drainage ditch and flowed 500 meters to a tidal canal.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The SCADA system was directing sewage valves to open when the design protocol should have kept them closed.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Initially this was believed to be a system bug.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Monitoring of the system logs revealed the malfunctions were the result of cyber attacks.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Investigators reported 46 separate instances of malicious outside interference before the culprit was identified.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The attacks were made by a disgruntled ex-employee of the company that had installed the SCADA system.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The ex-employee was hoping to be hired by the utility full-time to maintain the system.
[src:plc-scada/scada] In April 2008, the *Commission to Assess the Threat to the United States from Electromagnetic Pulse (EMP) Attack* issued a *Critical Infrastructures Report* document which discussed the extreme vulnerability of SCADA systems to an electromagnetic pulse (EMP) event.
[src:plc-scada/scada] After testing and analysis, the commission concluded: "SCADA systems are vulnerable to EMP insult.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The large numbers and widespread reliance on such systems by all of the Nation’s critical infrastructures represent a systemic threat to their continued operation following an EMP event.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Many vendors of SCADA and control products have begun to address the risks posed by unauthorized access by developing lines of specialized industrial firewall and VPN solutions for TCP/IP-based SCADA networks as well as external SCADA monitoring and recording equipment.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The International Society of Automation (ISA) started formalizing SCADA security requirements in 2007 with a working group, WG4.
[src:plc-scada/scada] WG4 "deals specifically with unique technical requirements, measurements, and other features required to evaluate and assure security resilience and performance of industrial automation and control systems devices".
[src:plc-scada/scada] The increased interest in SCADA vulnerabilities has resulted in vulnerability researchers discovering vulnerabilities in commercial SCADA software and more general offensive SCADA techniques presented to the general security community.
[src:plc-scada/scada] In June 2010, anti-virus security company VirusBlokAda reported the first detection of malware that attacks SCADA systems (Siemens' WinCC/PCS 7 systems) running on Windows operating systems.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The malware is called Stuxnet and uses four zero-day attacks to install a rootkit which in turn logs into the SCADA's database and steals design and control files.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The malware is also capable of changing the control system and hiding those changes.
[src:plc-scada/scada] The malware was found on 14 systems, the majority of which were located in Iran.
[src:plc-scada/scada] In October 2013 *National Geographic* released a docudrama titled *American Blackout* which dealt with an imagined large-scale cyber attack on SCADA and the United States' electrical grid.
[src:plc-scada/scada] Both large and small systems can be built using the SCADA concept.
[src:plc-scada/scada] These systems can range from just tens to thousands of control loops, depending on the application.
[src:plc-scada/scada] However, SCADA systems may have security vulnerabilities, so the systems should be evaluated to identify risks and solutions implemented to mitigate those risks.
